reviewText: Interesting and creepy at the same time.

Oh, where do I start?  First off, I'd really rather give this movie a 3.5, but I'll round up because it's got so many good actors in it.  I'm really not sure how this movie has flown under the radar?!  You have Ryan Reynolds, Rosario Dawson, AND Scott Speedman?!  That's 3 very well known actors, but I haven't heard anything about this movie?!  Either way, let's get into it, shall we?

My one MAJOR complaint (not sure if this is considered spoiling or not - be warned):  This movie jumped between 2 different time periods without so much as a hint that it was happening.  There was no character development before you were thrown into it, just BAM! and you're there.  I was very confused on what was going on or even who some of the characters where during the first 30 minutes.  Luckily, after I realized what was happening, things were very simple to follow.  I really wanted this movie to be a 5 star film, but there were parts in the movie that only seemed to be included as time filler.  Other than that, the acting is TOP NOTCH!  Production is very well done and the story itself was interesting enough that I never felt bored.

Final Verdict:  Definitely watch it, once!

"The Captive" is not your usual "B" film kidnapping/imprisonment film. The beginning is a bit confusing as it utilizes flashbacks which I didn't realize for the first 30 minutes, making this film a confusing mess to begin with. I will briefly sort out the first 28 minutes of the movie. If you don't want to know...stop reading.

Cassandra (Alexia Fast/Peyton Kennedy) goes missing from the back of her daddy's truck cab. Matt (Ryan Reynolds ) her dad becomes suspect number one to the Niagara group "Anything For Love" headed by Nicole (Rosario Dawson). Matt's wife Tina (Mireille Enos) blames him and turns against him. Jeffry (Scott Speedman) who is part of Nicole's group is openly hostile toward Matt.

Cass has special privileges as a captive and provides her captor with a unique service which makes this film a bit different. Matt tries to find Cassandra on his own (better than when OJ went looking for the "real" killer)  while the group works without Matt.

The film makes for a good "B" movie. It over utilizes the flash backs and really should have never had the flashback scene near the end which had me scratch my head...but wasn't she? How did? Oh a flashback. Of what? A day? A gimmick they really didn't need. Or was it a trick?

A four star film that was cut to three stars by the director and editor.

First off, I feel the need to warn my fellow (Ryan Reynolds; The Change-Up, Mississippi Grind, Deadpool, The Voices) fans out there.  This is not a Ryan Reynolds movie.  It's more of an ensemble cast featuring Rosario Dawson (Rent, Alexander), Scott Speedman (Underworld, Duets), and Kevin Durand (Resident Evil: Retribution, Smokin' Aces, Mystery Alaska).

This film definitely took Reynolds out of his comfort zone (i.e., he didn't play himself or anything even close to it).  He plays a father tortured by distrust and guilt.  After leaving his young daughter alone in the car at a pie shop, he returns to find she has vanished.  Reynolds does a more than convincing job falling apart as he is bombarded by accusations from investigators who think he was involved, blame from his wife, and the grief and disconnection any parent would experience under such dire circumstances.

The story then fast-forwards 8 years, when the investigators have come across images of whom they believe to be his kidnapped daughter...alive, and deeply embedded in an online pedophile organization.  Yeah, they went there.

The guilt and blame get pretty heavy, but I never found myself impressed with the story.  Reynolds character ends up in an uninspired chase scene finale and then things get resolved a little too quickly and conveniently for my taste.  I enjoyed this movie but, honestly, I think it's just because I enjoy watching any Reynolds movie.  It was also interesting seeing Kevin Durand play something other than a big, strong, tough guy.  I guess this film allowed both of them to shine their acting range a bit.

Stark, frozen landscapes give this film the bleak quietness that reflects the tenor and hopelessness, surrounding the subject matter explored: child abduction, blame, guilt, desperation, and organized pedophilia.  This portrayal of a chilling reality, leaves the viewer feeling more than a bit uneasy, and unsettled by its final scene.  Kevin Durand exudes a quiet, meticulous depravity, so well played, that it will be hard not to see him as "that guy", for some time; kind of like Mark Harmon trying to escape his role, as Ted Bundy.  Were it not for unanswered questions, loose ends, and "figure it out for yourself", shifts in the timeline, this film might have gotten another half star, from this viewer.

"The Captive" starring Ryan Reynolds as Mathew, father of abducted daughter Cass, portrayed by Alexia Fast, had a slow beginning for the first third of the movie. The setting was gorgeous in the Canadian backdrop of a snowy landscape and a somewhat lush Niagra police department. The natural greenery against the pure white snow gave a hopeful feel to this pallette; then the pallette turned to slushy, dirty snow which allowed the viewer to feel the dirtiness surrounding the pedophile ring Detective Nicole, portrayed by Rosario Dawson, and Detective Jeffrey, portrayed by Scott Speedman, ultimately brought down.

** SPOILER ALERT ** The actors did a very good job in their respective roles, although this viewer felt the plot had some gaping holes in it. No explanation is ever given as to why Mika, portrayed by Kevin Durand, watched Cass's mother or wants to hear sad stories from people; Durand gave a superbly creepy performance, however. Young Cass had been stolen and held captive for eight years, police searching for her - and the entire thing is resolved in the last ten to fifteen minutes of the film with no explanation as to how the police suddenly were able to find kidnapped Detective Nicole with no confession or help from shot and dying Mika. No real answer as to why Cass's hints to her dad about their last conversation, word choice of "gimmick" over "trick", helped him solve the case. The final third of this film had plenty of action, yet felt too rushed as it moved to a happy ending without viewers seeing what happens. Perhaps these jumps were left on the editing room floor.

This wasn't the greatest film in the world, but it was an interesting and entertaining way to spend almost two hours so this viewer is comfortable giving the movie a single thumbs up.

It was decent, but the ending felt extremely rushed and anticlimactic. I never felt like the characters earned their victory, but rather that it was given to them via super plot power. It also made NO sense why the cops didn't believe the dad the entire time, even though the guy went full vigilante and they knew about it.

There was a serious misuse of multiple timelines that could've been worked into a wonderful twist ending (there's no twist at all), but ended up being thrown out halfway in favor of linear storytelling. All the while baiting you into thinking there's the potential for a twist ending or some purpose behind the multiple timelines, which I expect out of good psychological thrillers.

Acting was strong in this. Everyone did a great job in that respect. The daughter had some weak points and was probably the worst acted (followed by the randomly introduced and awfully written hitwoman character), but played her role pretty well.

Overall, it was a hodge podge of decent ideas behind a pretty excellent premise (a child abduction ring not used for porn, but watching people's true anguish at the loss of their abducted child). I'm just sad that none of the movie was written or executed in a way that took that premise to the next level.

So, you're just going to steal the trailer off the truck of the guy whose daughter you kidnapped 8 years earlier because he happened to show up to a job sight that was shutting down due to snow and he also happened to be towing a bunch of pine trees that you then use to lure him to a unnecessary reunion between the before mentioned kidnapped young woman and her father, all the while hoping that the cops won't wonder why you're stealing this guy's stuff or maybe say, wonder why you're leaving a bunch of pine trees down the middle of the road.  What would've have stopped the guy who got his trailer stolen to just call the cops, then he and the cops follow the trail of trees to the kidnapped girl and her kidnapper?  Movie over at that point I guess they needed another 20 mins or something shoved in the middle.  I'd like to see the original screen play to see the story, which could have been good, to see if the story was ruined by poor direction or production or whatever, because half of this movie made no sense at all and could've been so much better if someone had just asked a few common sense questions, like why the hell is this in the movie at all.  It was like they had a bunch of ideas that had nothing to do with the story, they just wanted to work them in, so they through them all together around a decent plot, but instead of making one cohesive story line, it's just a bunch of disjointed premises that make no sense at all to the overall story.  Very poorly written.

I will admit I watched it twice. I'm the kind of person who avoids watching movie trailers altogether because I like to experience a film without any preconception. Over all, the film does keep you on the edge, thinking, "What's going on? What's gonna happen next? Is this person guilty? Is that person part of the bad guys?" It's kinda funny that some of those thrilling reflections in the movie-watching experience are IN FACT the result of poor writing and editing. I would also agree with the other reviews that the plot felt a bit slow, and then suddenly rushed in the end. Going between 3 different time periods does get confusing--some captions or black/white contrast would've been nice. In regards to Reynolds, it's probably the first time I've ever taken him seriously as an actor. I actually forgot it was him, which was nice for a change!

The cinematography and the landscape are incredible, the acting superb.  But don't watch this movie if you want a straightforward crime movie.

I frankly Loved this movie. For a person who writes at times on a blog about missing children and historical events related to it, this kind of movies help me better understand what is under the skin of someone capable of doing what the character does in this movie. It also had the psychological side of the victim. Something that many movies don't portray, they only portray the fear, the anguish, but not the fact that this child can seriously be mentally ill in the aftermath of something similar to what happens in the movie. Even the pace while speaking has changed. It is admirable the work by its director, the actors, and I would say the whole cast. This movie has another pace as well, so if you are expecting just an action movie only, you will be deceived because it has its own way of developing, reminding me some great movies by the Cohen Brothers or some North European style. I like this movie very much. It gives something more than just being a movie. I would love to develop more but I don't want to write spoilers.

The plot was kind of weird. I was disappointed with the lack of abuse (I don't mean full sexual violence but general abuse or torture) that movies like this usually portray from a kidnapper to the kidnapped) but was also pleasantly surprised that there weren't images or videos of child abuse shown even though a child trafficking ring was mentioned. Probably since that's a sensitive topic for most people.

It also seemed like the captor was mentally underdeveloped in his understanding of children and of sex, which happens all the time when it comes to pedophiles in real life; but it would have been nice to see something in his house in a separate room, or something where he fantasized about children and had a lay out of children and where's found them. Or anything to show that he had a child trafficking ring going on.

Another thing was with the cameras, how the hell did he get them everywhere? I was wondering throughout the entire movie how the captor was able to see and watch all that was going on. This leaves the watcher a bit confused as to what's really going on sometimes. Yes, he was following the family for a while to kidnap Cass, but how did he start following them? How did he find a way to get into the places that allowed him to put cameras where he wanted to watch her mom, the detectives, and other people/places?

I'm into psychological  thrillers so for me the suspense of some parts of the film I enjoyed, as well as the chase to find Cass and bring her home permanently. The ending left a bit to be desired but it was quite nice, having Cass end up in a place she revered as a home. outside of her home and fading out to the credits.

It's fascinating how bad this film is -- bad on all fronts: acting,  writing, direction, and editing. There's a curious mixture of auteur chutzpah (Atom Egoyan wrote, directed, and, I believe produced the film) and confusion over where to take the story. The incompetence at every level is too annoying to make this film remotely compelling or entertaining. Despite the intentions of Egoyan's script, no one in it is sympathetic, menacing, or attractive. I can't recall a more uncharismatic ensemble put in a film. They're all given such ridiculous things to say and do that each actor humiliates him or herself on screen.  Really a fascinating waste of viewing time,  valuable only as setting a new standard for how bad a film by a respected director can be.

This is one of those movies where the trailer is actually better than the movie. It had so much potential but immediately fell short right from the beginning. This is a movie about someone's child being kidnapped however they didn't show the kidnapping into well after the weird exchanges between the police and the parents were showed. You need that connection between what happened between the parents the loss of their child to set the tone for where the characters are coming from and so you can get on board with it. Then the "ring" that was supposedly exposed - a "ring" of what? I can assume what it was but if you are going to open up a story about something as horrible as the kidnapping and exploitation of children in our country then don't bring us there and then skirt around the issues. A clear concept of what was going on could have been done without graphic details. The best part - Ryan Reynolds.

I'm really not sure about all the other reviews. Yes it is a boring movie, the one cop is weird, and it goes on way too long - but I thought all the actors were good (Ryan Reynolds being my favorite as always), and I could understand the story. They went back and forth from different points in time, but they set it all up for you in the beginning. There is the time when the daughter gets kidnapped, 6 years after that and 8 years after that (which is now). The movie jumps between those 3 years.

SPOILERS:
As far as those that said they couldn't understand the movie: Father leaves daughter in car, daughter gets kidnapped and put into a weird trafficking scam for eight years. Meanwhile the detective in charge starts to get too close to solving the trafficking source (kidnappers), so they kidnap her. The daughter comes up with a plan to get the kidnappers caught by setting them up. The dad figures out who the kidnappers are and gets the police involved, then the police find the kidnappers and the daughter, which then leads them to the detective. In the end the bad guys die and the kidnapped detective and daughter are rescued.
Not for the faint of mind.  A well-done and presented movie covering a dark subject that will twist your brain and wrench your gut, especially if you have young children.

I was really impressed. The acting was good but I think that the directing and production made it in to a great psychological thriller. The fast pace and circular time/event changes made it a great roller-coaster. I believe that it is hard enough for a writer to make changes in time and place but to have it come across so well in film is even more amazing.  The producers and editors did a phenomenal job making cuts and transitions under director/screenwriter Egoyan. I'm not a big Mireille Enos fan and every time I have seen her acting it is basically the same character. Her character should have been played by someone who could have developed it more.  I think she needed to be strong and wounded, not just weepy and lost. Ryan Reynolds and Alexia Fast did good jobs at mixing things up and creating characters unique to The Captive. Not to spoil anything but there is a chase scene that was realistic. Meaning, the character Matthew did everything that I always say that I would do in a real-world situation. Again, good directing and production can do wonders,

Big Ryan Reynolds fan since long ago. I must say this was just short of a train wreak you just had to keep watching. The flash backs and flash forwards got to be a bit much, especially since there were no warnings about them. One scene would be present day the next woukd be 8 years earlier then the next would be present day again. Ryan plays a distraught honest caring Dad but at times seems unstable. Rosario Dawson is another great Actress who does good in the role but there are so many scene changes it was just too much to follow. Hollywood seemed to rush this script out and it seems they were writing it as they were filming it. Such opportunity to make a great film and to utilize Ontario,  Canada's beautiful scenery , yet stuck to a few cold snowy roads, couple diners and one or two Construction developments in the area. I give 2 Stars simply for Ryan and Rosario. Best part about the whole thing was being a Prime member and saw it for free. Id have been upset dropping 14.99 on it or heaven forbid had to drop 20 on tickets plus concessions. I think Ryan owed someone a huge favor for this 2014 flop.

I honestly love these types of movies! Ryan Reynolds and Mireille Enos were heartbreaking to watch and drew me into the story. The other actors were good but their performances suffered because of the way the story was told. Bouncing back and forth with the time really disjointed their performances and confused me more than it helped the story along. Especially since the actors all looked the same during the present and eight years in the past. Some noticeable changes would have been beneficial to the overall plotting of the story. Anyway, it kept me guessing, when I thought it would go one direction it veered in another way. I feel like there were several moments, scenes, that were missing that extra emotional impact that connects us to the film. Empty scenes that could've been pushed further to make this a really great movie. It had a better outcome than it could have had or that I expected it to and the ending was tied up too quickly. Overall it just fell short. I'm giving it 4 stars because of the unique story and the acting from Ryan and Mireille. But really, it's going to be a forgettable film.

This movie came right out of the gate with a suspenseful story and kept me engaged ALMOST throughout. That much it did well. The flashbacks were a bit muddy, as there's no real indication of when the story changes time lines, so you're left guessing at some points until a little ways into the scene. They could have done a much better job expanding on the antagonist. I still have no idea who he was in connection with the main characters or their society in general. So you're left accepting him as just another affluent psychopath. The ending was EXTREMELY forced. The writers abused the concept of deus ex machina to a point I've rarely seen before. You're heavily invested in these characters and pointed toward what promises to be a pivotal twist in the story arc and suddenly the movie is over and (without giving too much away hopefully) you're met with the cookie-cutter ending you'd expect. If the movie had been another hour long they could have done a much better job, but in the end they spent too much time on a lot of useless scenes. While most of the filming was very well done, I feel a lot of this movie should have been left on the cutting room floor and replaced with scenes explaining more of the subtleties that present throughout. Also, the plot spans 8 or 10 years, but it's always winter. It's as if nothing happened to this family the other three seasons of each year. There's even a scene where the daughter asks her captor "is it Spring yet?" Appropriate question. But no. It's apparently never spring. After watching it, I had that feeling you get when you watch a movie based on a book and you know there was a lot of suggested material that would only be understood by those that read the book. But this movie can't even rest on that excuse, as it was written strictly for the screen. Worth a watch for some great acting from Reynolds, but don't expect to be wowed.

I feel bad knowing that many people put serious effort and time out of their lives into making art and it is amazing that a film even gets made considering what has to happen to get a finished product. But hey, I go to work every day, and I work hard, too. So here goes.
A ridiculous script.
A crime and policing procedural with no actual procedure or policing presented or explored.
Deeply incompetent detectives in a specialized high profile unit.
A kidnapping and pedophile ring with significant resources, alive and well for years, abducting and killing, but in a city of about 80,000.
Secrets as an angle when never would that occur under such circumstances.
One of the worst film scores Ive heard in decades of movie watching. Irritating, indicating, and blundering. Tonal dissonance, suspensions, and other musical techniques used to generate an emotional reaction in the viewer through exposure to sound, specifically anxiety and tension, but only results in irritation and anger. A score that is ugly, neither evocative nor suspenseful, and often is laughable given what is taking place on the screen. Music can never replace an empty script with actors talking but not really saying anything. Probably only about 40 lines that had any real content.
An abductor and ring that gets loads of screen time without any backstory, but are caricatures of high school play creepiness.
The crime and pathology is bad enough and deserve serious attention when explored in art. The film is unwatchable. The cast deserves compassion and understanding, particularly Reynolds, Speedman, and Dawson. Im sure, particularly Reynolds, who is trying to move into delivering on some serious acting potential and develop a serious film career, and Speedman, who is already there as a serious film actor, but still looking for material (and choosing wrong in this case), thought that they were going to make a major, cutting edge criminal psychology film with a challenging, unnerving theme and showing the effects of loss, grief, guilt, helplessness, hope, and justice in the aftermath of an unthinkable, terrible event. What they got was a, literally, line by line weak script and an overall mess. The final straw is the decision to chop up the time line. Rarely a good choice and with no content to the script to support the choice  it actually works against the project. Time to move on, with lessons learned.

This should have been a great movie. Ryan Reynolds gives an excellent performance as the father of a missing child. Mereille Enos does a fine job portraying his wife, the mother of the child. Rosario Dawson is always really good and she delivers a solid performance here as a detective trying to figure out where the child went. The overall plot is pretty good and the individual scenes are nicely done. But the movie's awful.

It's awful because it jumps back and forth through time, with no hints to the audience about the timeframe it's currently showing. Is this scene eight years ago? Two weeks ago? Who knows? I don't know whether the screenwriters did it from the start, or the director (also one of the screenwriters) did it in post-production, but somebody broke this movie. It's as if someone wrote the scene designators on cards, shuffled the deck, and presented the scenes to the audience in that random order. The result is a movie in which current scenes make no sense, given the scenes that led up to them.

I enjoy complex stories. I don't even mind time-jumping as it can help build tension and reveal past details on an as-needed basis. But this... this is not that. This is really stupid. This movie is full of 'Huh?' moments for no other reason than that the decision was made to present it in a bizarre, nonlinear fashion with no way for the audience to keep track. It's a runaway rollercoaster with no safety restraints, throwing viewers out of the story at every turn and (maybe) picking them back up at the next loop. After almost two hours of disorientation, the viewer's just glad when it's over.

And that's a shame. Because it really is a compelling story. And the actors and crew worked very hard to get it right.

Egoyan is a bit of an acquired taste, I know, and this particular work took a serious drubbing by the critics.  But, this is somehow both a more accessible and a more horrific take on one of his most common themes, the loss of a child.  Despite This time, the emphasis is on the parents of a young girl who's been abducted by a pedophile ring.  But instead of the pedophiles being the gritty working-class monsters we've come to expect from so many films and news stories, these monsters are upper-middle class sophisticates with money and technology at their fingertips, and it's the parents of the stolen child who are the working-class zhlubs whose lives are at once shattered and yet fully-realized by their child's abduction.  The title refers to both their daughter and to them:  she is held captive by her abductors, while the abductors keep tabs on the unaware parents and their grief, turning them into another trophy from their crime.  Most of the story is set during winter, with the pristine expanses of white serving as a snowy metaphor for lives frozen by grief.  And who else but Atom Egoyan would have a macho actor like Kevin Durand sing the Queen of the Night aria from "The Magic Flute" in an earnest falsetto?  I give him a star for that alone.  Yes, certain story beats and dialogue beg our indulgence, but I found them worth it.

One of the worst movies I've seen in a while. Even Reynolds, who - in my opinion - is a great actor, couldn't save it. Telling stories out of sequence has been done well, and it's been done badly. This is an example of it being done (very) badly. As far as I can remember (and I watched this yesterday), the only thing that changed significantly was one character's hair length.

Sadly, the police attitude and pure incompetence was the most realistic part of this dreck. Basically (without spoiling anything, I hope), a financially-strapped man (played by Reynolds) stops to get a pie on the way home from his daughter's skating practice, something they do every week. She stays in the truck (lying down, because skating practice (which the police NEVER understand)) and when he gets back, she's gone. Because she was lying down, no one saw her, so he can't prove she was there. For eight years, the police never waver in their suspicion's of his guilt, so they never try to find the girl, except as part of their ongoing fight against online predators. Apparently, he reminds one of the detectives of someone in his own past, but - unless I blacked out - they never explain anything about it, even though this resemblance is the main reason the the cops never bother to investigate the kidnapping of a 9-year-old.

This may be a spoiler. But dang if I know. Meanwhile, the girl has been held captive (get it?) by a soft-spoken opera lover. He's tired of her now, of course, as an adult female, but he keeps her because she has other skills that he values (one of which IS a spoiler). It appears that she has convinced him to keep tabs on her parents and let her see videos in exchange for her telling him stories. Or is he having fun torturing the mother and getting a different kind of jolly by making the girl watch and tell him stories about them? Either way, she records these stories for him, and her Scheherazade gig is keeping her (and her parents?) alive. He forces her to re-record one story with "less self-pity."

I appreciate that they don't show any kids in creepy situations with adults, but they barely get the story across through exposition: the soft-spoken man is part of a ring of pervs. He's moneyed and might be in charge of security for the group. The girl, Cass, after years of abuse (they don't say if it is at his hands only), and eight years away from her family, doesn't appear to be damaged at all. She's convinced her soft-spoken captor to let her see her father and talk to him, and gives him a message that he eventually figures out that leads him to someone connected with the ring.

And still, meanwhile, the idiot cops are plundering around, still thinking the protagonist sold his daughter to pay off debts. Every time he encounters them, they insinuate that he's the key to the whole case: if he'd just come clean... The time sequencing is messed up here more than anywhere. It's been 8 years, but at one point, the wife - who visits with one of the cops every year - says it's been six. So is there an extra time period in there? Several characters are thrown in, who only succeed to show us how terrible the cops are at their jobs. It was like they took an episode of L&O:SVU and just mixed up the sequencing. Blergh.

When we finally put it all together about 40 minutes in we were appalled by the handling of the subject matter and the twist that just made it that much more sickening. These types of movies should have warnings posted regarding the subject matter. My husband and I watch R rated movies that are massively bloody and violent - but THIS movie took a revolting subject matter and skewered you with the deadness & fury of those trying to stop it as if you should see it as scraping dogs*** off your shoe. Just another day of walking through a life of utter depravity that you are numb to.

Thought it was very good, Reynolds and Enos do a great job portraying two parents who had their daughter abducted. Enos being watched by the kidnapper just proves how many sick individuals there are in this crazy world. I've see documentaries how child advocacy groups go inside these chat rooms and track certain user nicknames to try and link these predators to one another. Of course, the police check out the parents first, just like in murder cases. It usually is a family member who molests their kids, their nieces and nephews.
I believe this movie showed just how dark and disturbing police work can be in these cases, the things, us normal people, wouldn't think what these pedophile groups will do. Grooming girls they've had for years to help catch younger girls.
No, the writing may not have been Oscar material, but it showed us the things these perverted groups are capable of doing. I'm sure they do things we normal people couldn't fathom being done to developing young children, physically as well as emotionally.
No one who's ever lost a child, the way Reynold's and Enos' characters have, could begin to know how the real parents who lost their children in the same way have gone through.

Very underwhelmed by this film. Though it has a great cast, they battle with a script that is flat, flat cinematography, flat characters and dialogue, and over-complicated plot devices sprinkled with scenes and characters that are flat out unnecessary.

Ryan Reynolds is supposedly our main character, yet there are heaps of time we spend with our supporting roles that do nothing to further the plot. Rosario Dawson, who is usually amazing, is given a role that is built up to be important, only to deliver nothing in the end.

(Spoiler) it would have made more sense to have her character escape the van and end up helping save Cassie and Ryan Reynolds, rather than have her be magically discovered by the same police department who can't do anything right except be able to visualize puzzles that aren't put together (again, a scene that was contrived and had absolutely no point since that character did nothing later in the film).

The writer should have learned more about detectives and police protocols, and tried less to force down everyone's throats the idea that everyone believes Ryan Reynolds is the kidnapper, even though the motive forced on us is weak, and is stupid to think 8 years later he would still have her captive. But again, the detectives are so stupid in this film that that is the only suspect and motive they can ever think about.

But, if you like a good eye roller that continually makes you say out loud, "what is going on? When is it now? What the f---?"--this is your film. You'll be left wondering why the edit jumps around in time, especially since there is no solid indicator of what period you're in. It's a game! Present day? 13 years ago? 8 years ago? 6 years ago? Does it matter? Nope.

The bad guy looks like what everyone thinks a pedophile looks like so there's no surprise.  I kept waiting to have the daughter's hints connected to how her father figured it out, but that never materialized.  No explanation for the woman who kidnaps the detective and no apologies from the cop who accused RR all along.  A film with much promised, one that is shot beautifully, but doesn't deliver on the plot.

A disturbing movie that proved to be very interesting despite a few puzzling moments. Ryan Reynolds is really pretty convincing in his role as the father of an abducted child, and the villain in this story is creepy enough to keep your attention.  Many of the actors have French-Canadian accents, which would probably work out just fine except, unfortunately, the actress who plays the distraught mother of the missing child mumbles unintelligibly much of the time.  The story suffers from poor/unclear transitions from the present to the past and back again numerous times, so trying to keep the story straight is a challenge until the last half-hour. That said, it is worth watching if you like suspense, a story with some weird twists, and can handle a film that involves a missing child.

This movie sucked. The story was fragmented at best and the choice to jump throughout the timeline without footers leaves the viewer confused as to the order of the events. There are also a ton of variables that don't make sense, from cameras in multiple hotel rooms for more than 8 years, to teeth that were placed under pillows of a 10 year old (who lost all their baby teeth 2 years before), and to career detectives that get drugged by strangers at a social event. I think the writing was weak, and I feel bad for the actors. It was a strong cast with Reynolds and Dawson, but you just can't fix bad storytelling with famous actors. Better script, better writing = better movie, and if you can get an A-lister than that's a bonus. Overall, worst performance I have seen by Reynolds, and I am offended that an actress of Dawson's caliber took this role. DO NOT WATCH THIS FILM!!

I passed over this movie numerous times before finally viewing it.  There was something about the plotline that left me wondering if it would be too dark or  depressing to watch. My appreciation for Ryan Reynolds kept bringing me back to it. I am so glad I did. This truly stellar performance by Reynolds is perfectly matched by the intense delivery of Mirelle Enos.  A tragic and heart wrenching portrayal manages to keep an undercurrent of love and hope deep below the blatant decimation of their marriage through mutual grief that causes Reynolds to suffer yet again at the emotional onslaught from his wife.  Kevin Durand gifts us with a stellar performance that could easily have been overplayed but the subtle nuances and quirks in his performance makes the surreal situation believable and the characters create a flow to the plot and script that carry you along to the very end.  I highly recommend this movie for the performances and the emotional journey.

I watched this movie, only because Ryan Reynolds was in it, and I love him, but I had no idea what it was about when I found it.

After watching the entire movie, I still wondered what it was about.

This movie was all over the place, back and forth from the present to eight years earlier, and it was very difficult to follow the story.
This movie lacked emotion a movie like this should make the viewer tear up, but the acting was very poor, and the general feeling of the movie was just dull and flat and dragged out.
This movie was full of holes and left me with a lot of questions.

At the beginning of the movie, it was unclear who the characters were and what was happening.
Throughout the movie, and even to the end, I was confused.

I didn't care about the characters.  Every character in the movie just looked bored.  The kidnapped girl (Cassandra) didn't look unhappy or afraid of the pedophile, and although she said that she missed her parents, I didn't feel that from her because her acting was so poor.  She seemed bored yet comfortable, singing and playing the organ and being on the computer.  I didn't even care if the pedophiles got away with everything, because it wasn't even clear exactly what their crimes were or who was in charge of the pedophile ringit was only clear that the ring was large and the police were clueless.

I could feel Matthew's pain regarding the loss of his child, but Tina just appeared angry and depressed.  The way that Tina (the mother) and the two detectives blamed and suspected Matthew (the father) was disgusting.  It appeared that Matthew was the only one who really cared about finding Cassandra, and he absolutely did not appear to be guilty of anything (such as being involved in his own child's kidnapping, or "selling" her, or her murder).  No one thought for a moment that Tina might be guilty of anything, when there was no reason to think of her as any less guilty than they thought of Matthew, but the two detectives harassed Matthew and gave way too much sympathy to Tina.  Tina and Matthew did not appear to have any family or friends to help them, or for the police to question.

The two detectives (Jeff and Nicole) didn't look like they were were working too hard, and they didn't appear to care about their work.  They both seemed disgusted with their jobs, more than driven to save children.  When they met, there were no sparks between them.  Jeff said that he liked women with brown hair and blue eyes, which Nicole did not have.  Nicole was Jeff's boss, and she looked unimpressed with him during his job interview, and she appeared to begin working with him just because there wasn't anyone else available.  Suddenly, eight years later, they are at home together as a couple.  They had no chemistry as a couple, and it looked like they ended up together out of convenience.  Maybe it was too cold in Niagara Falls to go out dating, so the two detectives just settled for each other.

At the beginning of the movie (the movie is so badly out of sequence order, that the beginning had scenes from the movie's end), Jeff questions a man (it is not clear who that man is, but we see him with the pedophile a few times) regarding Nicole's disappearance.  But we never see Jeff or Nicole interviewing anyone about Cassandra's disappearance.  We all know that when a child is kidnapped, the first few hours are critical in finding the child alive, but these detectives did not seem to do any frantic searching or questioning or investigating.

Nicole seemed to be more of a social-worker to Tina than a detective...I didn't understand the purpose of Nicole's meetings with Tina.  Those meetings didn't seem productive in any way, so I didn't understand why Matthew was encouraged to attend.  The Police Department appeared like it was located in a rundown small town rather than in Niagara Falls (even Matthew said that it didn't look like a police station).

The snowy scenery was beautiful, but after a few scenes, it got annoying seeing so much constant cold.  The movie made a big deal about the black skate and white skate, but that whole thing made no sense at all to meCassandra seemed to try to use the skate colors as a clue, both to Matthew and during her story-taping, but no one seemed to get the meaning of Cassandra's hints (and I sure didn't).

Matthew worked as a landscaper, and we only saw him piling pine trees into his truck.  Tina worked as a maid in a hotel.
Why was the pedophile videotaping Tina cleaning hotel rooms?  How did he manage to hide videocameras in all of the rooms that she cleaned?  How did he even know which rooms those were?  How did he manage to constantly get into the rooms to leave little objects like a hairbrush or pinwheels? He didn't seem to "watch" any of the people who rented the hotel rooms, but only Tina.  It would have been more believable for the pedophile to use his skills and energies and money to hide cameras in a daycare center or anywhere where he could watch children.  Then he could have "stalked" children and kidnapped them.

How was Cassandra kidnapped, in a quiet and open area in broad daylight, vanishing in just a few moments, without even the sound of a car or car tracks in the snow, and no one seeing or hearing anything, even a scream?  How did the pedophile move all of Matthew's pine trees out of Matthew's truck and then pile the trees neatly and evenly spaced down the road without anyone seeing anything?  What was the point of the pedophile allowing Cassandra to meet with Matthew for five minutes? And why now, after eight years?  "To make her happy?"  How could it make her happy to see her father for five minutes, then watch him get shot unconscious, and then have him ripped away from her again?

A woman in a wig poured a powdered substance into a drink at a crowded dinner party, and no one saw her do it?  There were many glasses on the dinner table that looked so much alike, so how did that woman know that Nicole would drink from that glass, and that no one else would drink from it, or that Nicole might even order a new fresh drink instead?  The dinner was to honor Nicole, but no one at the dinner cared about how Nicole was getting home - - didn't she have a limo waiting just for her?  It would have made sense for Jeff to show up at the dinner party late, or even go there at the end to pick her up, so what if they had an argument, they were in a relationship for eight years, and he should have gone to the dinner party.  What was the point of having Nicole kidnapped?  What was the pedophile planning on doing with Nicole?  Why not kidnap Jeff also?  Why not just kidnap another child instead?  The pedophile ring appeared to be so powerful that Nicole and Jeff were nowhere close to even suspecting their identities. (Nicole sat at the table with the pedophile during the dinner, socializing with him as if she respected him and looked up to him, but it was not explained who she believed him to be.)

A man named Willy is arrested, and the pedophile visits him in prison, but their conversation does not make sense, and we never see Willy again to find out what happened to him.  What was the purpose of the short scene where Matthew picked up a hitchhiker?

It wasn't clear what the pedophile did with Cassandra.  I could guess that he kept her locked in a room for eight years, raping her.  It was implied that she was forced to make kiddie porn movies.  Then it was loosely explained that she was used to lure children through the Internet to be kidnapped.  But the two detectives didn't seem to be working on finding endless kidnapped children.  Cassandra had access to the Internet alone in that room, but she never tried to contact anyone to get rescued.  Reviewers will probably say that it is the Stockholm Syndrome (like the true story of Jaycee Lee Duggard).  But Cassandra didn't even care about reaching out through the Internet to save the children that she was helping to kidnap, and she didn't care that she was key in causing other children to go through what happened to her.  It didn't make sense that Cassandra was the only one whom the pedophile held "captive."  It would have made sense if there were other children trapped down there with Cassandra or if Cassandra was moved somewhere else.  In other words, when Cassandra became "too old" to interest the pedophile, it would have made sense that he would have put another girl in her place and moved Cassandra somewhere else.  The scene at the end, where Cassandra was reunited with her parents, was just not as emotional as it should have been.

I am sure that there are more questions and plot holes that I missed.
I just know that I was confused throughout, and I barely knew what I just watched.
The ending was a mess.

A very good idea, with very good actors, in search of a movie that got lost somewhere in the editing.  I think the title of the movie was meant to be "Stories" and then that plot line used.  I think this is a good example of what happens when you do an artistic endeavor as a committee.  Starts of great ideas became lots of lose ends.  The slips and slides of time are ok, you don't necessarily need to put up a neon sign, but they needed more clarity.  Can someone tell me if we lost the female policewoman?  She was supposed to be killed but ends up in a talking van?  How does all this voyeur video fit in with the bad guy's motivation and personality?  The daughter was one-dimensional; she was making up sad stories but wasn't affected?  Maybe it was me, but the "gimmick" was also a potential good idea that was lost.  The key idea of a gateway was great but lost.  Nice production value, loved the idea of a high-end capture, loved the use of snow.  Worth watching...but you will have to watch it more than once.

From an acting and cinematography view, the film was good.  I felt the actors did a good job, which is expected noting the names used in the film.  I felt the story was interesting, but it did not paint a gritty/real picture of children trafficking/kidnapping such as something like the film "8mm"; regardless, I will buy into the story of individuals with perversion and power kidnapping children feeding off their emotional hopelessness as well as that of the parents.
  Unfortunately, there was a lot that I could not accept.  Why would someone meet their parents for a time?  For that sense  of hope?  There is too much risk.  No one would attempt such a thing.  Noting how the villains had no issue attempting to kill individuals later in the story, it would explain that they would not be bothered trying to do so earlier on to reduce the risk of their plans being discovered.  These components in the story caused eye rolls.
  Finally, while some found the movie "Memento" to be genius, it is only because telling a story out of order made sense noting the viewer was perceiving the story much as the confused lead character who had mental issues.  Telling a story such as this one in such a fashion is unneeded and actually detracts from the story; it aided the story in no possible way, and it certainly was not clever.  That falls on the producer and director to rethink their ideas.

Starts off like an A movie, with elegant settings, good lighting and sound, adequate acting, etc, then the plot descends into a disjointed lump that left my wife and me resentful, at the end, that we had wasted our time. The same guy wrote, produced, and directed it, and the story and its telling come off as amateurish, like vanity productions often do, because there's nobody telling him he's making a mess. The premise is strong, but this telling is full of wonderful plot possibilities unexplored, gaping plot seams, unanswered questions, and opportunities missed. Even the "payoff" is limp.
So what if *The Captive* is free: Your time is more valuable.

When you have one movie to watch every 2-3 weeks, "The Captive" was an unfortunate waste of time.  The beginning was unintelligible and the end was just, well, it just stopped.  The plot line sputtered along without any larger story to follow.  The theme was compelling enough to invite a large viewership but deserved better writing and production.  Character development for Reynolds and the two detectives was fair, scene production was fairly well done, but it was so poorly written that I could never recommend that anyone waste their time with this movie.

The truly good thing about this movie is that it only somewhat portrays the super-sick world of pedophile predators, not a few of which are indeed wealthy people who get off on the total power kick. (Check out the Lawrence Franklin Scandal [covered up by the FBI in DC] and all the child sexual predators in Washington, DC). The acting was only average, and the only believable character was Cassandras father, Ryan Reynolds. Rosario Dawson has really good natural Hispanic beauty, but is an unremarkable actress. This movie also makes me think what a travesty it is that more public awareness is not given to this sociopathic world of child predators. The best thing that I would do to improve the script was for the cops to have shot the Mika, the pedophile, in his leg to adequately down him, and then pistol-whipped the creep to find out where his partner was. A much needed vengeance kick at that point. They could have scripted more to show how they were able to find Dawson in the van. The ending of the movie was rather lame after the decent suspense they manage to build at that point. The best thing that I take away from this movie is that I am going to insist that my church keep missing and exploited children in the weekly church bulletin prayer request list. I can imagine that what really goes on in the sicko world of child predators is not something that any director could honestly portray in a movie for the public, and I hope I never see anything that actually goes on in that evil world.

Just finished watching this movie, and am literally speechless. I would give this travesty ZERO STARS if possible. This crap show should be screened at film schools across America as instruction on how NOT to write a film.

The non-linear progression of the story is does not lead to any sort of reveal, only confusion.

Time has apparently zero affect on the world our shallow, and undeveloped characters find themselves trapped in.

There is literally zero character arc; which is not all that surprising given the fact that entire key elements of the subject matter at hand are wholly glossed over.

The happenstance which takes place in order to tie characters together is so unbelievable it is truly mind boggling that anyone could be so stupid as to write such utter nonsense, let alone that this garbage was actually produced.

Ryan Renyolds is the only redeeming aspect of this movie, and spoiler alert ladies, he never takes his shirt off. In fact, I am not sure if he ever has a wardrobe change. Its as if he, and all of the other dimensionless characters wear the same outfits for 9 years, which is literally how long this movie felt to endure.

The use of flashbacks makes the flow of this movie disjointed and confusing. The characters were poorly developed. The background score was annoying. There are so many questions left unanswered. It gets two stars for Ryan Rynolds acting.
worth five stars

Even on Amazon Prime, I can't believe I wasted 2 hours of my life.  Horrible, predictable, wannabe thriller, with zero sense of care for any of the characters (Ryan Reynolds is barely the small exception).  This move sucked.  The casting director followed the same, annoying recipe, dictated by those who feel there aren't enough leading roles filled by African American women (and I'm talking about a leading detective role).  Follow that up with the even more offensive, lazy, young, white doofus, to portray the back-up detective role.  I have nothing against any of the actors, it's the delivery of that recipe that is so very old.  These audience betrayals happen, while trying to tell a hideous kidnapping story by jumping back and forth between an 8-year timeline, often leaving you wondering where we are supposed to be.  One thing to keep in mind, if the writer/director wanted to fulfill MEANINGFUL and BELIEVABLE ROLES, one should do some research and make those more believable.  8 years pass by and we are supposed to believe that none of these detectives got a promotion, or moved around into other units or positions within the department?  It's weak, and offensive to the actors who took on those horribly casted roles.  Not a single one of them foiled the crime.  Spoiler alert, it's Ryan Reynolds.  Such a sad, cookie-cutter movie, that should have been left for a network tv show storyboard.  That's all this is.  A long, 2 hour tv soap opera, with crappy acting and a bad mix of characters.  Ryan Reynolds does a good job playing the father, but he's got zero supporting characters or a good enough backstory to allow any viewer to really care.

Somewhat Off topic :
Another reviewer complained about how the police were acting in the beginning and unfortunately it was all too real. As a victim of a violent home invasion I was treated much like the character in the movie. The cops kept asking why you? why your house? This is never a random act. Yeah okay lets see I lived in a over privileged zip code , on a dead end street that had 10 houses on it 2 acres or more for each house and it was a rainy day. Had it not been raining that day I would have been at work and it would have only been a B&E, bad guys didn't expect me to be there so to me this screamed prime target with a prime opportunity all on its own but they didn't want to hear it. Hours went by before they really started working the case with me being the victim and not as an involved party.

Simply put - I sat riveted to the movie because I like it.  Now, did it have holes that didn't get filled?  YES  Did it need more explanation?  YES
Child abduction is a parent's nightmare.  When this happens to the parents who clearly doted on their daughter, the first hole was dug.  Cops didn't develop well in the story, wife did not develop well in the story, child story had potential but only partially developed.  Father was most developed character and got the worst deal from his wife and cops.  Enjoyed Ryan Reynolds for the most part of a grieving father and finally at end got some brains to get his daughter back but the ending just left me questioning ( a niggling way back in the mind there was something suspicious about him)

He kept his vehicle just like it was for the eight years she was missing.  Why did he clean out the things for 8 years he held sacred in his truck once his daughter was saved? Why was the remembered conversation she had with him brought into the plot 3 times?  It bore no relevance to the situation.  To be honest the movie left a question (s) suited to a part 2 or at least a few clues more revelation in the trail of credits, that has directors doing to see if you stay around till the last name rolls off the screen. Sometimes you learn more about the movie if you stick around to the end of the end.

The portrayal of events in this film is a great idea in theory, but not well executed. There is no indication for the viewer of what is foreshadowed and what is present day, and by the time you figure it out you're a bit too frustrated to care what happens in the end. What you could predict, however, is in fact what happens. No great revelations; very disappointing. Not an award-winner by any means for Ryan Reynolds.

Such people are more susceptible to unwholesome influences and may be more inclined to act upon them to the detriment of some unfortunate soul.  I recognize that there is no way that I can see to limit the production or consumption of material that imposes negative influence.  Nevertheless, I regret that suggestive negative content like this is now a sizable norm in our collective fare known as "entertainment".

Once you finally get your bearings in this film it happens, you realize that there is no climax. The film goes about a linear projection and leaves you disappointed and confused. So last week I went searching for snowshoes I went all over and never found any.  I went to try and find a dress for this thing with a dinner I was going to go to.  I worked and oh yeah my dog totally ate my homework.  There was this one time I was hanging out with my friends, oh that's it.

Confused yet!?  Yeah me too after watching this movie!!!  Which is about all the movie does.  It has a never ending supply of flashbacks, You turn around and yup you guessed it another unnecessary flashback scene.  I could never figure out what in the heck was going on.  Then it gets you all the way to the end and you think you are finally going to have closure and figure out what the heck is going on.... WRONG!  That's it movie over.  This movie felt like chickens running around with there heads cut off.

The story line was all over the place.  You never did figure out how any scene really linked to another.  what was the point of the kidnapping, why did they want all her memories? Why were they videotaping the mother?  It was a mess and a complete disaster!!
 Acting was good considering what they had to work with.  I so badly wanted to like this movie because  I love the actor Ryan Reynolds but this movie was such a mess it was hard to like anything about it.  Just do yourself a favor and don't get caught up in it.  Don't Watch it I promise you won't have missed out on anything spectacular... in fact you won't have missed out on anything at all.  Just find another movie and move along!

Eight years after their 9-year-old daughter Cassandra went missing, her parents Matthew (Ryan Reynolds) and Tina (Mireille Enos) are to know, in a different way, that their daughter may be still alive. Told in a chronologically shuffled order (like some of Christopher Nolan films), Atom Egoyans thriller attempts to captivate the heart of viewers, but except the star Reynolds effective acting and beautifully shot landscapes, the film fails in doing so.

I think I see the directors intention of focusing the impact that the sudden and unaccountable absence of someone would give to us  and I have seen some of the directors films including The Sweet Hereafter  but even so, The Captive is not very convincing either as a thriller or a drama, with flat characters lacking reasonable motives.

You see, in The Captive, a police officer (played by Scott Speedman), who should be polite and calm in dealing with this kind of delicate case, is incredibly rude and stupid. Kevin Durands one-note character walks and talks like a villain from a Victorian novel, with monster written all over him. In short, people just don't act that way.

Egoyans previous effort Devil's Knot was criticized for not telling us anything new about the case it depicts. Maybe so, but it is still ten times better than watching the badly written potboiler that makes little sense

The honesty of acting in this movie was gripping, edge of seat sensational and deeply moving. The acting and directing shared very real, shocking and sad glimpses of the psychological realities that these particular types of child abductors feed on. The subject material of child abduction was played out with a thoughtfulness and respect for the portrayed victims and the inevitable suffering that the families shared, with a new awareness of these types of crimes. After discovering that these crimes can happen (in minutes, even seconds), one can only hope that our society at large, will become more concerned, vigilant and informed in stopping these crimes from happening. It was very satisfying to watch the undoing of a criminal mindset and see the criminals caught.

If you're a parent don't watch. Okay so I didn't read the reviews or know anything about this other than seeing the cover come up time and again on my suggestion list. And while I will say the the story is interesting and Ryan Reynolds does great drama acting (he's not just action and comedy!) The story line hit a little too close to home. I have two little girls of my own and this movie will probably give me nightmares for a while, just like any child abduction does story now that I have kids. Aside from Mr. Reynolds acting, there is little else that I liked about this story and oh so many plot holes. I won't list them all here, but here are a couple of whoppers:
What small town police office has a team of +/-6 people working internet child porn only? Granted this takes place on in Canada so maybe it's a little different there okay.
Who delivers a trailer full of trees to be planted when there is a crap ton of snow on the ground and more falling? The ground is frozen stiff, it's Niagra not the North Pole. Spring still comes to that part of Canada, or at least it did on the American side.
If you're captured, and you regularly have long conversations with your capture, alone, and he leaves the door open, why don't you hit him over the head with something and try and run for it? No attempts to escape at all.
The worst part for me was that both parents keep getting reminders of their missing girl, obvious, blatant reminders, and neither one calls the cops? EVER? It takes pinwheels, of all things, to get the mom the get the cops involved again. Not a skating trophy "like the one [their daughter] won", not a tooth that could have been used for DNA, not even a tranquilizer dart shot into the Dad?!?!? Come on people.
Well okay, the actually worst part was the totally crow-barred way in which the Dad finally stumbles into finding the captures. Clearly an after thought, as many things in this movie seemed to be. Time and time again it seems like the writing team was sitting around the table and someone would spit-ball an idea and they would all be like, yeah I like that, lets see if we can work that in here somewhere. Take out the whole bit about the female cop, beginning to end, and the related useless arrest of that one guy, and take that probably 15-20 minutes and put it into developing the little girl's side of the story. Why does she do some of the things she does, why doesn't she do some other pretty obvious things (see above), when did the parents fall out, one minute their fine then all of a sudden they are divorced. I could just keep going on and on and on.

SO MANY loose ends in this movie I can't even begin to explain them all. Some people show up for 2 minutes and you never hear about them or their role again. Spoiler alert: Cass acts like she can't go/leave with her dad when he finally finds her, but at the end when she is actually rescued she goes back to normal and everything seems fine?? Most people that have lived with a captive for that long probably wouldn't go back to every day life like that, especially since she made it seem like she couldn't leave her new life earlier in the film. I got finished watching and felt like I still had a million questions that they didn't bother to answer. This would've been better as a TV series or something that could string the audience along and then actually give answers at the end! Only reason I gave it 3 stars is because I love Ryan Reynolds.

Actually, there *was* one single "redeeming" feature about CAPTIVE -- the brief but interesting synopsis provided by Netflix, which would likely have proved sufficient enough to arouse the curiosity of any film buff and compel him or her to rent it.

The pretty Canadian snow provided the only possible relief from the monumental tedium of this turkey, which jumped from one disjointed (often confusing) scene to another.

Perhaps the biggest letdown was the total lack of character probing of the twisted psyches belonging to the twisted child abductors; however, at the end of the film you fully realize that the entire twisted crew responsible for this twisted abortion would have failed miserably at this endeavor, as they failed so miserably at everything else.

Purchase this film *only* if you're besieged by some perverse craving to throw away good money.

The story circled around with the father, mother and the detectives on finding the girl with psychotic predator who takes pleasure on doing weird stuff and playing with emotions of the victims. This movie made me more aware to become more careful and vigilant as a parent and learned not to leave my daughter ever again alone in the car even if they are already 10 years old coz we'll never know who is watching our kids. Captive is a film that would have been way more enjoyable to watch and maybe a little easier to follow if it was filmed all in the same timeframe.  Instead we're in the present, we go back to the past, we're back in the present, we're back in the past.  It is just really annoying and one of those where you go oh hang on is that girl supposed to be that child who was abducted?  We also know that another character gets abducted because we have an unnecessary scene near the start with her poster where our one of the most incompetent movie cops ever blames another character for her disappearance.  It would have been better if that was a surprise when it happened as would a lot of events.  The film also has a lot of whispering and mumbling, it's hard to know what characters are saying, especially at the start when it's important.  You also wonder what was the point of some scenes such as the jigsaw one? Where we are introduced to a superhero powers like child crime fighting team, but when the small town's you would imagine biggest case occurs, they aren't used, and instead it is left to the incompetent rookie who immediately blames the father because he reminds of someone who was mean to him in the past and the rookie's trainer.

There's also a lot of questions that are never answered in the film, primarily why was the girl now grown up being kept alive and not killed, when we know there's been plenty of people killed and buried by conversations from the ring members?  Also since he's no longer into the adult original abductee, and kidnapping is so easy, surely he'd have another child locked up somewhere in the house?  Also you can't help think wondering why doesn't the adult version daughter just over power the skinny wussy abductor, hit him with any thing in the room and run up the stairs and out the door to freedom.  Even the nine year old version probably could have overpowered this guy.

This isn't a bad plot over all, and the concept of a child abducted and still around as an adult when the abductors no longer desire it as a bedroom toy but still serves some other purpose for them is an interesting one, however this part of the plot really goes into no depth at all and isn't explored or revealed to the viewer to any satisfying extent. There's even another character in this situation but again we learn nothing about her. The end ten minutes or so are interesting and have a bit of action but it's a slow mumbled mess viewing experience getting there. The villains' schemes, such as the tree one and even the original kidnapping rely on Ryan Reynold's character not turning around, using the bathroom, not looking out a window when you would imagine something that would have made some noise is occurring and for no one else to drive by the whole time you're planting trees on the side of the road where there is no where to pull your vehicle and the trailer over without impeding traffic while doing so.

If the timeline had been a linear one rather than jumping back and forth the film would have been more enjoyable, easier to follow and would maybe have rated a little higher.

Ryan Reynolds has shown exponential growth as an actor of late, and his performance in "The Captive" is no exception. The travesty of this film is that it dangles over the precipice of being a good film. Good acting all around, with Scott Speedman as the weakest link as the pseudo-cowboy detective, who just wants to catch the bad guys with his own sort of street justice, and his perpetual look of befuddlement at every turn.

The film begins powerfully from a visual standpoint, and then takes a turn for the worse, in story and in syntax. The timeline of the film is a jumbled mess, and we never quite know during which period of time we are actually watching, until its too late to care. Just as soon as it starts to make sense, the it's confusing again, and that's not really the worst of its sins.

In a nutshell, the film is about an estranged husband Matthew (Ryan Reynolds) and wife (Mireille Enos), who have lost their daughter. One day after ice skating practice, daughter Cassandra goes missing from the back seat of dad's truck while he goes into a roadside diner buy a cherry pie. We soon discover that (years later) Cassandra is working for an underground ring of sicko deviants, who are using her to lure other young girls over the Internet into their fold. The big mistake here, was the length of time spent showing the kidnapper discuss strategy with his victim. These segments are over indulgent and quite honestly eerily pandering, which seem to portray the perpetrator in a sympathetic light - this does not do the film justice.

There are some very good moments, but unfortunately not enough of them to classify this as a good film. If you're in the mood to watch a psychological thriller about a child gone missing, watch the incomparable "Prisoners" instead, and leave this one out in the cold.

While I do love Ryan Reynolds and think his performance was pretty solid, the movie plot and writing was rather meh. The movie starts of nonlinearly, which only serves to confuse rather than as a useful storytelling device. After we finally get onto the "real" timeline, there are then unexplained time skips between scenes where you are only able to know what time you're in because the characters keep saying "6 years since she disappeared" "8 years since she disappeared" etc. If you're going to make it that blatant, just put a scrawl at the bottom of the screen that says "2 years later". All of this basically makes me feel like the producers read about nonlinear storytelling, thought it was a cool idea and did it with no understanding of HOW to use the device correctly.

Aside from that making things a little confusing, the story itself is lackluster. There's no real mystery to it at all, as the only "suspect" the cops ever have is the father himself. Which on many levels is incredibly infuriating beyond the obvious of making the cops look completely incompetant. It's like: a girl is missing and you spend hours interrogating the dad? They don't even *think* he could be telling the truth? And the one "bad" cop guy is suspicious because he thinks no kid would ever lay down in the back of a car? Yeesh. They try to explain this "bad" cop guy's dislike of Reynolds by saying he "knew a guy like him" once that he was investigating, but again the writing falls short because we never find out what "guy" he's talking about or how that case went wrong. Just hollow character building.

And the worst part about the whole movie to me is the mother's hate towards Reynolds. She of course blames him for their daughter missing, despite the fact that it makes no sense. Maybe at first in the heat of the moment, but jeez really lady? And of course it doesn't help that the cops are basically pathetic and can't do their jobs, thus placing blame on the dad as well.

Anyway, the story is lackluster, there's no real mystery to solve since the kidnapper is revealed from the very start and the cops have NO OTHER suspects, ever. And even the kidnapper makes no sense. Obviously he took her because he was a pedophile, but then still keeps her because... she apparently agreed to help lure other kids in? But oh, don't worry, she's still a good person and is not psychologically messed up in any way.

Not as bad as most reviews here if you don't already know the plot. The symbolism in the storyline serves well to build suspense and keep the viewer engaged. The back story fill-in technique works well enough. This story is as much about the psychological trauma that an event of this magnitude would create, so the complexity, confusion, distrust, blame, and irrational behavior that the parents and police go through is believable and appropriate in my opinion. I can't think of another movie quite like this one so I have to give it a star just for originality. I thought about the movie days after I watched it so I have to admit that while not forgettable, some of the ramifications in the storyline are disturbing.

We were looking for something to entertain us one night on Prime, and stumbled across "The Captive" - which neither of us had heard of before...  The number of 'stars' (recommendations) associated to this film made us a bit curious, and since we're both Ryan Reynolds fans we thought we'd take a look ...  And while the theme of the film centers around some fairly 'dark' concepts (child abduction and potential sexual abuse) we thought it was an excellent film.  And then we both commented about our curiosity that we HAD never heard of this film before (... but then, arguably we're probably not the most 'current' when it comes to some films, and since I believe this is a Canadian film which may not have had a particularly wide distribution, well... there's no doubt to us that's why we 'd never heard of it).  But we believe it is yet another display of Ryan Reynold's talent and acting capabilities.  Combine his art with that of Rosario Dawson, Kevin Durand, Bruce Greenwood - and for that matter the entire cast, and it is sure to make an impression on anyone.  A really entertaining film - and no doubt Kevin Durand makes for one very despicable villain, absolutely. .... Had us on the edge of our seats right up to the end...

This movie does a good job of addressing a serious topic that needs more attention.  Conveying the heart ache and turmoil that accompany the abduction of children is, I'm sure, a difficult thing to do.  Mireille Enos brilliantly portrays the multitude of conflicted emotions a mother must endure in this situation.  Ryan Reynolds commands your attention with his role as the devoted father now desperate to save his little girl.  Their relationship is entirely convincing and tugs at the viewer's heart in every scene.
Peyton Kennedy and Alexia Fast make the role of an abducted captive very intense and believable.
The movie's use of fast forward and flash back in time is both effective and makes watching the film exciting.
Bad guy Kevin Durand is creepy and convincing while Rosario Dawson exemplifies a dedicated and compassionate law enforcement professional who maintains focus and is compelling as the "good guys" team leader.
The basic plot of the abduction of a 10 year old girl who is held captive for an extended period while her mother and father keep hope alive and suffer unimaginable emotional pain is an awful reality for too many families.  This movie is about that subject which is the stuff of parent's nightmares.  The well directed cast delivers characters that make the story very real by keep the pace spot on.  There were good plot twists and surprises without detracting from the main story line.
As a parent it was difficult to watch but I recommend it to other parents because I found that it challenged me to be more vigilant.

I must first confess a bias toward this film because I like the work of its writer and director, Atom Etoyan. I am similarly, favorably disposed toward two of the movie's lead actors, Scott Speedman and Rosario Dawson, who are often consigned to secondary parts. In "The Captive," they are given enough screen time and dialog that they finally have room to shine, to show their talent in inhabiting a role so believably, they have become their characters. The other roles are equally well cast. Ryan Reynolds, whom I'd written off as merely a pretty boy, in this lead role surprised me with the depth and nuance of his portrayal. Bruce Greenwood is, as usual, stellar, and whenever he appears onscreen, every second, he makes count! Bravo to Etoyan for deftly humanizing a terrible crime and making it much more than a forgettable statistic. You are rooting throughout the movie for Reynolds' dad to reunite with his daughter, Cassandra, or Cass for short, a 9-year-old figure-skater who vanished while her father was buying cherry rhubarb pie to bring home.

You finally figure out what's going on, but that didn't help my opinion of the movie---it was annoying.

One other thing bothered me a lot.  It concerns the detective who decided to search for missing children even though he had an excellent record as a homicide detective.  The writer depicted the detective in such a negative light as though he had a vendetta against fathers.  If the reason(s) for his untoward suspicions were explained, it/they went over my head.

The three stars are for Reynolds acting; zero stars for everything else.  This was not a good purchase for me, and is now going into the delete bin.

We establish a pedophile ring that is advanced in "a way that has not been seen" that is very powerful and behave in new ways... but we end the movie after Ryan Reynolds gets his girl back after 8 years... by which point I stopped caring about that and was more worried about the ring that captured a cop and brainwashed a kidnap victim into fighting for them...

This is one of the silliest movies I have seen in some time. Whoever pieced this thing together must have been on drugs; or, perhaps they needed some drugs - those that control schizophrenia.

Why do directors and others involved with a movie that has great potential, like this one, not wake up to reality? For example: 1) A Dodge Ram truck that looks exactly like it did 8 years before and is intimidated by a wimpy Land Rover? Huh? 2) A dozen trees in the back of your truck can lead someone down the road? Huh? In reality it would take hundreds to accomplish the feat as shown in the movie. Even if the rendezvous place was right next door there weren't enough trees to leave a trail.  3) Totally unbelievable cops that question the father a few hours after the kidnapping. Huh? You don't start making accusations against the victim until you've got plenty to suspect and certainly NOT when they first show up to report their daughter is missing. At least Ryan Reynolds got to punch the stupid cop out in his driveway.

Then there's the wife who is miscast and you dislike for dumping her husband or at least abandoning him. Cops that have to end up romantically entwined when it's not necessary and the unexplained time travel jumps in the story that are too cool for their own good. SMH at the director of this movie.
