The movie was a disappointment to me. Although it had a lot of potential, but because of the nature of genre - psychological thriller - the director took too much creative license with the creation of plots and subplots upon subplots. By 3/4 of the way into the movie, I was having difficulty keeping up with the flow of plot and dialogue, questioning the introduction of every new scene and character, as to whether it was integral, or non-important, to the development of the plotline. At various points, it was impossible to discern who may or may not have had various motives, if any; again, this goes along with the concept of the psychological thriller, but for me, there was no logical, or even feasible, points throughout the picture to which I could anchor on and stay with the flow. By the time the movie was concluded, I was already disappointed, and the conclusion was meaningless for me.

I just got through this weeks-long movie, finally! (Is it still 2015?) I came here to write a review...a protest, actually. But many have beat me to the punch, and with excellent observations, too!  Here's what I'll add.

I was disappointed that I never got to know any of the characters as well as I would have liked to. They just weren't developed as real human beings. I didn't even get to know Ryan Reynolds' character that much, but felt a sliver of connection to him because he's famous and he got a fair amount of screen time. Still, the script didn't show much of who he was, beyond being a dad who lost his kid. That's not enough.

Reynolds may not have been famous at the time this was made, but still, to list him as a supporting actor? Really? When he carried the movie?

The parents' marriage was horrible--painful to watch. The mom's behaviors repelled me. Maybe that's how moms of kidnapped daughters act sometimes. I guess it could well be so. But it doesn't make for good entertainment.

Then what about the promo, which claimed this was "...a psychological thriller about a man whose only option is to plunge into a world of deceit." So he "plunged" for eight solid years? Didn't see much of that sleuthing happening on screen.

As for being a psychological thriller, the only mind game was having one's intellect artlessly tweaked and yanked by incoherence, while also put on grueling hold waiting for the "suspense" to take over in the jumpy story line. For me it was more like psychological detention.

Atom Egoyan makes beautifully understated films. This is perhaps his least understated. Unlike many of his other films, it actually resolves. Fine performances, and a story that can easily be followed, once you learn the groove and swing of Egoyan's editing style (which often jumps back and forth in time without warning). In the end, I was happy, but conflicted about my love for this man's films. This is the most commercially appealing film Egoyan has ever made, and I'm hoping he doesn't stay this path. If he chooses to do so, then his best films are most definitely behind him. I'm a cinemaphile, and I love directors whose films reflect a style they've been honing for years, decided, generations. I've always loved Egoyan. But if you're an Egoyan fan, like me, this one might leaving you wondering...

Like most of his films, this one deals with family, a parents love and devotion to their children, and family tragedy. But this is easily his most Hollywood-friendly attempt at expressing his themes, and I found it distilled, and almost "entertaining", in an almost forced kind of way. I don't watch Egoyan's movies to be entertained. I watch them for the place of contemplation and meditation they always bring me to. This is a good film, but when it was over, I didn't reflect on life, my life, the lives of others, or the very notion of being human, in the way ALL of Egoyan's previous films have made me reflect. In fact, by the end, I have to say, I'd forgotten I was watching Egoyan.

If you're a fan of this great filmmaker, see it so you can draw your own conclusions. it's most definitely worth seeing, and it's most definitely a very good movie. But be prepared to be left a bit perplexed at the end. Egoyan has always made untraditional, unusual films that are unlike other films. If you've seen his masterpiece, THE SWEET HEREAFTER, then you know what I'm talking about. This film is rather traditional by comparison. Almost "Hollywood".

And If you've never seen an Atom Egoyan film before, it's a MUST-SEE.

The way this movie superfluously used time jumping really demonstrates the insecurity of the movie makers.  It's almost like a french movie that uses a gimmick to disguise a horribly made movie and try to pass it off as "art".  This way they could tell the critics that they don't understand "art".  If they wanted to use a "time jump", they should've shot the first scene the way they did, then added the note "xx years earlier" then shot the rest of the movie in sequence.  That would've made sense.  But instead they go back and forth without telling us which just leaves the audience scratching their heads and confused the entire time.

Note to everybody who likes to make these type of "B" movies.  I know Pulp Fiction is a cool movie.  Stop trying to be like Quintin Tarantino.  Nobody cares that the beginning is the ending is the middle is the somewhere in between.  Or, if you make a crap movie, stop trying to cover it up with gimmicks then diguise it as art.

This has to be about the worse film since Sandra Bullock went full retard and - well I can't really say what she did because that would be a spoiler - in Premonition.

Bottom line, there's just not much that makes sense with this movie.  The main character is a landscaper, in Canada, where all we see is snow.  The main character's wife works in a huge hotel, but only cleans the same three rooms.  The bad guy who has kidnapped the offspring of these two, is weak-kneed and basically doesn't really do much until the end, and even then it's kinda like a last gasp.  Add to that a script that jumps back in forth in time just for the heck of it, and wooden performances that are about as inspiring as paint drying, and you have a real mess on your hands.

If you want something to put on in the background, then maybe this flick will work.  But if you don't want to be asking yourself questions about the movie every two minutes (Why don't the police investigate? Why doesn't the kidnapped girl try to escape?  Why does the bad guy take every risk in the book, just asking to get caught?), then I suggest you give this one a pass.

Put me solidly into the feeling of helplessness of a father whose child had been abducted. The suspicion of the police and wife, and the blame of the wife were all well portrayed. Monsters like the abductors in this movie exist. The whole thing just made me want to track down the animals who do this stuff to children. I really liked the fact that the movie portrayed evil without enacting it. Viewers aren't made to watch images or scenes of horrible things being perpetrated on children; it is all left to the imagination, which is absolutely sufficient. For instance, rather than showing the screens and images viewed by a cop while he's being screened for employment on a special child-abduction taskforce, you watch his face as he views the images. His reactions are all you need to see. You know the horrors he's watching and that the monsters that perpetrate them need to be stopped. You get it when he looks away, and you get it when the screener says it's their job not to look away. What a horrible, necessary, soul-wrenching, loyal, self-sacrificing career where there really are no happy endings, just endings to awful chapters in hard, hard stories.

It is getting harder and harder to find good movies to watch having to sift through the myriad of budget offerings.  "The Captive" was an engaging suspense drama that moved along slow at first, but give it time, it gets good.

The other night my husband and I were looking for a movie to watch on Amazon Prime, and we came across The Captive.
We enjoyed the movie.  However, it is very important to mention that it was a very different structured movie.  Unlike other movies
which would normally give you a hint when there is a flashback (some movies would have flashbacks in black and white, etc), The Captive
does not warn or hint when a scene goes into flashback.  It almost reminds me of stream of consciousness. You just might find yourself asking, "Hold on.  Is this happening now?" The Captive has a lot of flashbacks with no hints, but it is an interesting movie that keeps you captive, wanting to know where it is going and how it will end.  I won't say much about storyline because I don't want to spoil it for anyone.

I really wanted to like it.  I love Ryan Reynolds; he was excellent in this movie.  I just didn't "GET" it.  The whole premise, I mean. I've passed time in worse ways, though.

I broke my rule here of not reading reviews first and I should have read them because wow this movie is not what it could or should have been given the storyline and the cast.  The level of incompetence of the cops in this film is astounding and I wonder if its done on purpose by the writers or no one did any proper research. The cops are spoken of like they are highly qualified but its soon apparent that they have no clue how to carry a case or follow up on glaring information right in front of them. The one time when they might have caught a huge break in the case - the female lead breaks it up and exposes everything. What an idiot and she's supposed to be the 'expert'.  None of their tech guys or nothing in their line of work has apparently ever taught them that web cams can be hacked either.  I would expect this of the civvies but these guys are supposed to be excellent at what they do (NOT!)

They have made up their minds about Ryan Reynolds and it seems nothing or nobody else matters.

This could have been a whole different film and I'm not sure where behind the scenes this went off track but it not only goes off track it goes over a tall cliff like a really bad wreck. The editing is sub par - whoever thought that it was a good idea to jump around the storyline, in the manner in which they go about it, was dead wrong in their thinking. Its not that I cannot follow it but its like a really bad book where the author has no clue how to set the storyline. They have no idea how to jump around in a story with some sort of cohesion.

There is almost no sympathy on my part for ANY of these characters, especially when no one is allowed to engage the kind of screen time or enough of the storyline, to make them remotely interesting or to care about, except Reynolds and even then its a lukewarm feeling at best.

The wife is a shrew who has spent the entire time blaming and screaming at her husband. Reynolds is the only one who actively gets on anyone's ass about the case, while she is busy telling anyone who will listen that its her husbands fault the daughter is gone.
As to fault - I was upset with Reynolds when he goes into a business and doesn't even lock the doors on his truck, leaving his daughter inside.  I personally wouldn't leave a ten yr. old in a car even if it was for a couple of minutes - but as you learn later on, this was gonna happen anyways. It could have happened in the mothers care too. Seriously though you could have taken the wife out of this film and I think it would have been better - she added NOTHING to the overall film.

The abductor who is apparently a part of a much larger pedophile ring is sufficiently creepy but once again not a well fleshed out character (no pun intended) The fact that the cops take down another local pedo who goes to jail, they then miss out on a prime chance to not only get farther along in taking down the ring but their not even checking up on what visitors this guy might have. They are aware of this ring - they even remark on how well the ring is evading them with their super encrypted system - they drop the ball in such a glaring manner every time something is not followed up by what should be in-place protocol for a unit like theirs.  So yeah research for the writers - its a thing.

The end is a joke. The cops are once again showing a level of stupidity that is just off the charts, Predictable in several parts. And apparently the last scene is there to make you think that eight years of the wife being a total bitch is supposed to magically be cured by a family hug and its ludicrous.  Personally I think there were problems in that marriage way before the daughter got kidnapped that were never explained.

There are just so many, many mistakes in this film that you could MST3k it all day long.

Save your money or your free view on Prime and watch something else. There are several abduction films that are way better than this one.

I was very disappointed in this film.  I usually love Ryan Reynolds, but this film did not do anything for his career.  Reynolds' performance was actually believable as the distraught father, but the story line was very thin.  Also, I had a difficult time feeling any sympathy for the long suffering wife.  I was wishing someone would kidnap her as her character was ridiculous and I think that the movie would have been more interesting if they had chosen a much prettier actress to play the part of the wife.  A hunk like Reynolds should be paired with an equally beautiful actor.  It would have been a better story to have the husband and wife supporting each other while they both frantically looked for their daughter together -- but, that didn't happen.  In addition, I didn't think the villain was scary enough.  I never got the point of why he kidnapped the young girl.  Don't waste your time or money on this one.  Just not entertaining enough.

Of course, the father is suspect all along, but the ending is happy. While that may seem trite, the story is very realistic and carried out well, and it comes with a good lesson - don't leave your kids alone in the car, even for a minute. Story line wasn't terrible in and of itself.  However, if a movie is going to try and tell a story in a non-linear fashion, the writers really need to make sure that method is warranted first of all, and if it is, then they should ensure that it's executed clearly.  This movie in particular failed on both counts in my opinion.  In fact, the story would have been better served had the scenes been set in chronological order.  The confusion created by the non-linear decision is what moves this from a 3.5 to a 2.5.

The fact that I'm supposed to believe Ryan Reynolds is an outdoors/rugged guy is what moves it from 2.5 to 2.

All in all, not a bad movie if you're bored and scrolling through FREE streaming options.

I'm not blaming the screenwriters for this.  I'm going to blame an idiot film executive.  I wanted to like this movie and was excited to see it.  I like all the actors in it and I think they did a great job.  My problem is with the ending.  I don't want to give anything away, but there were a few major scenes that set up the whole premise for how the resolution of the kidnapping will take place.  None of it was used.  Nothing was resolved in the end.  I think an idiot film executive came in and said, "The movie is too long so we're going to do a different ending.  To write this ending, I'm bringing in my idiot nephew, Joe Doofus.  Mr. Doofus will reach into his special place and yank out an ending that negates everything previously built up in many of the scenes.  The ending will just happen, like magic, because, you know, films are magical.  Everything will wrap up in about 5 minutes and will seem like the ending for a different movie."  Perhaps Joe should have reached a little deeper into his special place.  I feel sorry for the actors on this one.  They still have my respect.

I hate giving this film four stars because the subjective matter for me in particular is very disturbing. Films about abducted children and their captures are hard to watch especially as a parent.  I try to avoid watching them but sometimes my desire for vengeance against these monsters pushes me through such films. "Captive"  reveals a sick side of the human race that's hard to look at. The acting is very good all around and Ryan Reynolds gives a realistic everyday man performance as a dad with a kidnapped daughter.

The film constantly keeps you on the edge of your seat. There is an ultra eerie quality to the actor playing the main abducter and you can't wait for him to suffer or die in some way. I can't say I came away from the film "entertained", just reminded of the stark reality of the evil in our world. One final point. Thankfully I did not have to view repeated acts of sexual abuse as the film strangely stayed clear of such depictions.

Liked this one more than I thought I would. It has some clumsy moments - neither of the cops is believable or competent, bit overall the movie struck just the right notes on the disgusting and evil networks of men who are pedophiles and child kidnappers/traffickers of young girls for online porn. Not surprisingly, it can be the prominent men of any town. It would've been easy for the  screenwriters and actors to go overboard emotionally on this one, but it was a fairly low boil look at how the middle class family and small Canadian town react over a decade to a girl who goes missing in the blink of an eye. My tween watched it with me and, as is often the case with pop culture, absorbed the stranger danger storyline in a way that we as parents often can't fully articulate is part and parcel of the adult male world that every young girl/woman has to come to terms with.

This was a much better psychological thriller than I expected so I'm pleasantly surprised. I knew I liked the acting of Rosario Dawson and Mireille Enos but wasn't sure if I'd enjoy the plot. In the film a family is torn apart by the abduction of their daughter, eight years prior. Using flashbacks, you get the before/after effect. During the annual meeting with law enforcement (Rosario Dawson) to check in on any progress, they discover that their daughter has been seen alive in a bizarre Internet ring luring other young girls to their doom. As the plot unravels there are twists and turns yet it seems realistic, even as the villains are a new variety of sick and twisted. Would recommend to anyone who enjoys crime shows.

The kidnapped kid seems quite happy with her situation, except when she's not. And as another reviewer pointed out, the mother seems to be quite ok and cost with the cops who haven't produced any results for her in 8 years, but seems to hate her husband who is at least looking for the kid. Finally, the climax was very lame. I expected something clever, but again, expectations turned out to be unrealistic.

Disgusting, idiotic, horrible. Will never watch another film written/directed by Atom Eogyn again. His script was utterly slack. I watch a lot of movies. My husband is an actor. You look for good scripts with a beginning, middle & end. A story arc. For God's sake. This had ping-pong back & forth in time BS, people speaking at barely a whisper, detectives doing the super annoying "comatose acting" (that's a real style now: people meant to act like they are dead). The creep who keeps the daughter captive in order to torture her parents (& this is a ring of people who do the same thing) could not have been more icky. We quit watching halfway through because this movie was simply so disgusting, it wasn't worth our time. If you were forced to read stories like "The Most Dangerous Game" in high school, you've already got the idea behind this film---mental torture, sadism, glee at seeing people in hell. I cannot fathom the mind that created this S***

The show is about a family dealing with the abduction of their eight year old daughter.  Again, the father is the main suspect but we are shown at the beginning he had nothing to do with the disappearance of his daughter.  The wife accuses him of leaving the girl for five minutes alone in the truck when the abduction happens.  Which is totally unfair.  They end up divorcing because of the strain of this situation.  The father (Ryan Reynolds) is given the opportunity to see his daughter for a brief moment, after eight years.  So he now knows she is still alive.  Good show, highly recommended.

We generally are suspect of R-rated movies and thought maybe this movie was going to be over the top in some way due to its R rating. However, after watching the movie, we are barely certain as to why it was rated R. The acting was just okay. What was difficult with this movie was trying to figure out where you were in the timeline. The movie is centered around a certain kidnapping. However, you rarely knew if you were in a time period BEFORE that incident or DURING that incident or AFTER that incident. As far as we could tell, there were no transition markers whatsoever in the movie to communicate where you were in the timeline. It became so frustrating that it was almost funny. Definitely things could have been a lot worse in this R-rated film and we were thankful that there was no graphic display of the evil perpetrated upon the captive by the nemesis. However, the move just sort of plodded along and just wasn't all that interesting. I gave it three stars because I cannot give it 2 1/2 stars and to be kind. The writing seems okay and, as I already mentioned, the acting was fair. We were glad we did not pay money to see this movie in the theater (did it show in theaters?!) or to rent it. It's definitely a movie we would not care to see again.

I think the background scenery played a huge part in it and maybe because it's rainy and gloomy day outside where I live; it was the perfect movie to watch. However, I do think it worked well with the story except of course the type of business Ryan's character had in it just didn't make sense. At that point, it was just a distraction and you feel as though it was a dumb decision on Ryan's characters part on choosing a career in landscaping for the area he lives in?! It's a silly distraction but the acting was very good. After clearing up the confusion of the sequences, it was thrilling, gut wrenching and my only hope was that it all worked out in the end like any other happy ending to a movie. This is a movie that is TWO hours long and has pretty much nothing happen. I really wanted to like this film - I had enjoyed a couple of Atom Egoyan's previous movies I saw ("Exotica" and "The Sweet Hereafter").
In "The Captive" he goes to his signature of broken timeline to add suspense / mystery to what otherwise is a rather flat and one-dimensional plot.
The ending was especially un-satisfying - he spent so much time building the suspense and characters and finished the story in the last few minutes of the film. Even that was extended by several minutes of police station re-unification and the father driving off somewhere.

I think the director has run out of ways to exploit his signature style and it all looks the same. The same sort of thing that's going on with M. Night Shyamalan - both directors can't seem to get away from their early signature styles that made them famous.

Just like one of the other reviewer's comments, quoting a line from the movie: "We don't need [the same] gimmick"

It wasn't bad enough to get me to hate the movie, it was just a little annoying. What did negatively impact my opinion of the movie was the male detective character and the acting performance given in the role. He was ridiculously serious at all times and his confrontational attitude towards Ryan Reynolds's character (because "he reminds him of somebody") is the absolute worst part of the movie. Totally unrealistic and not even the least bit believable that a detective would be this rude and unprofessional to the father of a girl who has gone missing.

In all, the movie wasn't too bad. Definitely entertaining and worth watching if you have some time and nothing else to do. Just wish they could have handled the male detective character differently.

One of the absolute best movies that I have ever seen.  Nuanced acting, wonderful story arc.

Two problems, though:

1) There are some extraneous characters who were not fleshed out sufficiently.  Namely, the employer and the woman accomplice.  This could have easily accommodated a 2.5 hour length with the added dimension and not have diluted the movie.  Instead,  it  I was left a bit frustrated with a few questions:  Did the employer know? If so, was he part of the network or just a voyeur? Was the woman abducted by this man or another person originally? Is she related to Cass's abductor in some way?

2)  The pacing of the story is too fragmented.  I realize that the director is trying to go back and forth between past and present.  However, it was too jumbled and actually distracted from the story itself.  The viewer should be able to focus on the action on the screen comfortably, without being confused too much.  There were times when I was trying too hard to figure out past or present, which left me unable to focus on interesting details that were happening onscreen.

All in all, an amazing movie. Ryan Reynolds at his best.  Scott Speedman deliciously competent yet creepy.  Rosario Dawson flawless. I want a sequel to tie up loose ends! This movie could easily be adapted to a series.

"The Captive" is a riveting drama with a thriller edge. Ryan Reynolds brought intensity to his role as the father burdened by guilt after his daughter is kidnapped. The film plays out in a series of flashbacks which provides glimpses of the heart of the story and the behavior of the actors. As it unfolds you are drawn into the anguish of the mother, played by Mireille Enos, who is filled with remorse and resentment at Ryan, holding him responsible for what happened to their child.

Although the pace of the film moves slowly, by the end of the movie the reason for it is clear. Without the deliberate slow action, it's possible that the viewer may not have fully understood the underlying reason for the title of the movie.

The film tackles a very serious problem of children being kidnapped for sexual abuse and pornography and how even the most visible persons held within the public trust to protect society can become involved in this type of activity.

While police authorities assigned to the case are obviously frustrated by the lack of clues in the disappearance of the girl in this small town, even they have no clue that the real villains are hiding in plain sight and the level of influence that they have. The two lead detectives, Rosario Dawson and Scott Speedman while working together have different opinions on how the case should be handled and harbor lingering doubts about the innocence of the father although no hard evidence implicates him.

The toll of the years that have passed since the kidnapping took place is obvious on the main actors in the drama. But the captors relationship with his captive eventually leads him to exposure because of his arrogance.

For me the real star of this film is Alexia Fast who plays the daughter who shows not only resilience and courage, but an acceptance of her captors mental state and the intelligence to outwit him to gain her freedom and be reunited with her family and continue pursuing her goal of becoming an Olympic skating champion.

Honestly I didn't know what I was getting into when I started watching this. Ryan Reynolds plays a grieving father who has lost his daughter to kidnappers. Eight years later, he drives around in the same vehicle that he owned when she was taken having lest the back seat exactly as she left it in a shrine to her memory.  He keeps in regular contact with his wife, who blames him--sometimes cruelly--for the loss of their daughter.

Really, I think it's Reynolds' performance that I found most compelling. I used to think of this guy as kind of a lightweight in the acting department, but over time I've had to concede that he's a cut above watchable. Sure, there are missteps like "The Green Lantern," but that movie didn't fail because of Reynolds.

Reynolds does a good job emoting the pent up grief of a frustrated dad. He's on an emotional hair trigger and you get the sense that he's just barely holding things together. However, he doesn't seem menacing, just that he's about to go all to pieces. It's easy to empathize with him, and when evidence that his daughter might still be alive begins to mount, there is a palpable tension to see these two reunited just to end the father's suffering.

Actually, when you watch it, compare Reynolds to the actress playing his wife. She resorts mainly just to hysterics, and although her performance is effective, I think Reynolds managed to more effectively convey an existence of constant pain than she did.

Yes, like I said, there is plenty in this film that is implausible, but it's got a good cast and there are some moments of real tension. It's worth watching.

There are several problems with the presentation of the story (the most obvious being the jumps back and forth in time without clear on-screen notifications for the viewer, pay attention to the first 10 - `5 minutes and its possible to get your bearings), and I went into the viewing having seen the trailer which helped me understand some plot points, but none-the-less I enjoyed it and praised its unconventional methods to friends.  Make the effort and you might be surprised.  (POSSIBLE SPOILER ALERT - The ending was very rushed.  They must have run out of money for Rosario Dawson's final scene in the van because that was damn fast.)

The movie is disjointed and has some obvious flaws, but some of the acting was good. I thought the chase scene was a cheap climax... it should have had a more suspenseful mind thriller ending. Creepy guys don't shoot guns or drive fast... they do creepy stuff. The best thing about the movie was Kevin Durand. He was right up there with Nicholas Cage on the "Creep Meter". Well done. He is married to Korean American actress Sandra Cho. Nicholas Cage is married to Korean American actress Alice Kim... hmmmm... I love these creepy characters... my wife is Korean American... there's something there worth investigating. Anyway, Kevin Durand's performance is as good as the best actors that play creepy characters. The way he held his mouth was so perfectly odd. Not a violent guy (that's why the chase scene didn't work for him), but a gentle almost empathetic sick individual. That is what made it so good. Kevin Durand gets a 10 on the Creep Meter. (Jack Nicholson, Steve Buscemi, Nicholas Cage, now Kevin Durand). Kevin pulled this movie up from a 2 to a 4.

This movie stars Ryan Reynolds (Safe House, Van Wilder) as Matthew and Mireille Enos (The Killing) as Matthew's wife Tina, whose nine year old daughter, Cassandra (Alexia Fast) goes missing after her Dad (Reynolds) leaves her for a few minutes alone in the back seat of his pickup truck while he stops at a local (and deserted) place to pick up a pie for dessert.
**Possible spoiler alert**
Eight years later, the daughter is still missing but through scene flashbacks, the story unfolds and the audience learns that she has become a recruiter for an underground child porn ring. She, herself, had been an unwilling participant in that ring until she became too old to be in demand and so was converted to the role of online child recruiter. She has never been allowed outside and has been locked in a downstairs comfortable room in a mansion. Her captor became attached to her. Rosario Dawson stars as the police official who suspects Ryan Reynolds, befriends wife Tina.

It was difficult to ascertain whether the scene I was viewing was in the present or the past. There were repeats of the ends of scenes from different perspectives which made identifying what timeline you were viewing more challenging. I have little patience for filming "gimmicks" like this. I cannot abide the acting style of Mireille Enos. She overacted in this movie, which is typical. After finding out that her daughter was kidnapped, she flies into a physical rage and attacks her husband, demanding answers and accusing him of all but arranging it. Eight years later, she loses it yet again and tells him the loss of their daughter is all his fault, hating him anew. Then, when they are reunited with said daughter, I threw up in my mouth a little bit when she plasters on a too bright smile and reaches her arm out to hubby. Poor man allowed himself to be embraced by her.

Excellent film, but my guess is that box-office-pampered folks might not think it's good. The film struck a careful balance between showing the dark and light sides of this issue without triggering the crap out of its audience. I saw in some reviews that "the bad guy could've been badder" or "it looked like the girl could've beaten him up anytime she wanted" - well, those who wrote that are blissfully naive. When this stuff happens to kids, the captors spend weeks, months, or even years convincing the children that they should stay put or bad things will happen, like "if you leave, our people have orders to shoot your parents/siblings," or "if you are bad then we will send your parents pictures of what [we make] you do," and so forth. If you're curious enough to have read this whole review, I'd say go ahead and watch the movie. Like I said, excellent, and also suspenseful; even though you can see a lot of what's happening, it keeps you guessing.

I never got bored, but that's about as good as it got for me.

I'm no film critic and I know nothing about acting or making films, but the flashbacks seemed a little hard to follow most of the time. I felt like I wanted a little more detail before it ended... like it was kinda half-baked. Ryan Reynolds, as usual, was fantastic... but despite his face on the cover, he's correctly listed as a 'supporting' actor. He felt 'under-utilized' to me.

The relationships between the parents, between the parents and the cops, and between the abductor and abductee all felt puzzling... as in "I've never seen anyone act so nonsensically ever before in my life." Overall the movie feels very disjointed. Lots of snow, but I kinda like snow, so that was fine for me. Lots of under-developed sub-plots: father gets accused of abducting his own daughter, then you never hear another word about it, or why he wasn't arrested or whatever. Father's business is failing, yet we see no sign of him struggling financially; only mention of it. Abductor has a very nice house with all sorts of gadgetry and works in a suit in an office that does WHAT exactly? No idea. His boss seems dodgy... then you never hear another word of it... the list goes on.
It had potential...  Just a little dry on the plot.

I really enjoyed this film. I'm actually shocked at some of the negative comments however each to their own. I thought the actor chosen for the lead criminal was just perfect. I read a few people disliked him and thought it appeared the girl could easily beat him up and escape. I don't think a child who was raised in a corrupt environment filled with blackmail and sexual abuse would be mentally healthy enough to even believe they could get away.

I thought the film was put together quite well despite some comments that it was pieced together from past, present, and future. However many popular TV shows (Blacklist, Scandal) and movies (Forest Gump, Avatar, The Notebook) use this method and they use some obvious changes to the characters appearance (a different hairstyle for example) to indicate a change in time. It had my attention and I definitely felt Ryan Reynolds did a wonderful job in this role. I say it's absolutely worth the watch!

How anyone could score this film higher than one is a puzzlement.  The only redeeming feature is the acting, particularly that of Ryan Reynolds.  The story, on the other hand, is like a drunken nightmare, disjointed and staggering down a dark, blind alley.  There are so many holes in the plot, that it literally falls apart when you look at it closely.  Who was the kidnapper's accomplice, for example?  Why were the investigators so dim-witted that one of them actually ended up being snatched?  How did the male culprit manage to weave into the high-class social scene so effortlessly?  This movie could have been much better -- perhaps even great -- with a little more intellect invested and some professional script editing.

The reviews are pretty well split down the middle for this movie, but I am glad I gave it a chance because I really enjoyed it.  Granted, the movie seems to be stuck in an endless winter, but clearly its meant to invoke the frigid, numb limbo these parents, who have had their child abducted, are trapped in.  The setting of this movie in the Niagara Falls in Canada added to the appeal of this movie for me: harsh, cold, immense and magnificently beautiful.  The setting evokes a mood, but that is probably where the haters lose the point.  Note to realists:  this is not a "48Hours" or "CSI" type of movie, where the evidence is scientifically examined and the professionals track down the "unsubs" and neatly tie everything up. Yes,  there are loose ends that could have been brought to some logical conclusion, but they are woven into this tale that  admittedly does take some jarring jumps back and forth in time, but they are plot twists that are not particularly hard to handle.

The cast is peppered with great actors, such as Rosario Dawson as the lead detective and  Ryan Reynolds and Mireille Enos as the parents, which is  another reason for not missing this gem.  Their acting is accused of being "wooden" by negative critics, but I challenge them to describe just how do parents whose child has been taken and is still missing 8 years later would behave.  The tension between the parents is palpable not only because the police are suspicious of the father but also because the mother blames him since the child was with him when she was taken.  I don't want to say any more because you should watch and decide for yourself.  Don't miss the haunting song played during the end credits, which we are given just a hint of during the movie and is another easily overlooked gem.

I really enjoy watching stories that involve a kidnapping or mysterious disappearance that later gets investigated.  The whole mystery of uncovering who did it? for what reasons? and so on, are exciting to me.  I can think of two movies that are similar in nature to The Captive (2014), and they are The Prisoners (2013) and The Vanishing (1993).  So if you liked the last two titles, than this Canadian mystery-drama should not disappoint you.  I have not seen a lot of movies with Ryan Reynolds, and the only ones that I can recall off the top of my head are his comedic roles.  However, in this film Reynolds is great at portraying a tormented father of a young girl who gets kidnaped by a ring of pedophiles somewhere in the snowy Ontario province.  The movie jumps back and forward in the span of 8 years, as two detectives are trying to solve the mystery behind the disappearance of the nine year old Cassandra.  One of the detectives, has even formed his own theory about the disappearance, and believes that the father was involved in it.
Can't decide what was the worst - cap guns, costuming, music, or the stunningly poor use of flashbacks.

One of the oddest (and oddly captivating--see what I did there?) movies in which you'll ever see an all-star cast of this magnitude.  The whole is decidedly less than the sum of the parts.  The film is on the verge of clicking at several junctures only to clunk to a thud.  It lurches backwards and forwards without keeping the core intact.  Great actors aren't allowed to develop their characters, which really gives the whole enterprise a two-dimensional feel.  Pacing is unbelievably slow, which can work if the storytelling is better.  I'm a notoriously easy grader when it comes to film, so I've probably overshot the average viewer by a star (or so).  It could have been a much better movie.

This movie suffers of misguided editing.  There are three elements to this movie: The Family, The Police, and The Capturer. I have seen movies re-edited in chronological order, (I'm thinking of Memento and Irreversible) and posted on YouTube.  I would like to see the same thing done to Captive. The premise of the movie was good; it had promise, but it fell flat.  The failure of this movie rests solely with the director.  There were too many illogical character interactions, too many unconnected dots, and too many unanswered questions.  Despite all that, I really enjoyed Ryan Reynolds' performance.  It was refreshing and quite a pleasant surprise to see that I love him just as much in a dramatic role as in a comic role.  However, his performance wasn't enough to save the movie.  Another disappointment was the grievous underutilization of Rosario Dawson.  With a better script, better directing and better editing, Ms. Dawson could have truly shined, and Kevin Durand's wonderfully creepy performance could have rivaled that of Ted Levine in Silence of the Lambs.  This could have been so much more.

Good God Almighty!.... a few weeks ago I was going to pay $6.99 to rent this movie I am so glad I didn't! Now that I saw that it was available on prime tonight I watched it This movie is all over the place! I had such high hopes..  the trailer looked decent enough but even the trailer looked disjointed. It looks like the writers and directors just threw bits and pieces of good movies like "Prisoners" "Ransom"  "Taken" and other great movies into a blender and hoped that something decent would've come out.  I'm left with a whole lot of unanswered questions like what the significance of the "gimmick" about the black-and-white skates was?

Since it's free now on prime I guess if you curious to watch it go ahead but don't pay for it you'll regret every dime you wasted. I've seen worse but what a waste of such great talent of some great actors, Scott Speedman I like but  I really couldn't stand him in this movie; they make you really want to hate him. And who in the hell was the person that Reynolds reminded Speedman's character of?

A frozen waterfall is seen many times in 'The Captive'; it is visible through the windows of a hotel room, where Cassandra's mother is working as a maid. Years after Cassandra was kidnapped, objects with very specific emotional links to the missing girl keep turning up in that room, and she's beginning to question her sanity. Director Atom Egoyan carefully keeps that wall of ice in frame throughout these scenes. It's a powerful image. For the parents of a missing child, it's like life freezes over, and time has stopped; all that water, all that pressure, just frozen in time and space, waiting for the thaw... in this case, as the years go on, it becomes less and less likely that 'the spring' -- the resolution, a break in the investigation -- will bring good news. But in order for the waters to flow and fall, there has to be an answer: a girl who is suddenly a teenager, or a collection of bones in a shallow grave. Until then, they live life on hold. frozen in place, all that weight crushing down without relent... Or something along those lines. Cassandra's father, Matthew --  Ryan Reynolds, in a moving performance -- is tortured by guilt, ashamed that when he went into a store to buy a pie, someone stole his daughter from the back seat of his truck. In the film's standout performance, Mireille Enos (from the TV series 'The Killing') portrays Tina, a mother whose pain is so acute it threatens to destroy her; she is unable and/or unwilling to help assuage her husband's suffering, and uses that moment Cas was taken as a weapon to hurt him further, as if the more pain she can inflict on him, the less she'll feel herself. Matthew bears his wife's bitterness, and the baseless accusations, much better than most people would, I think.

Atom Egoyan's latest film returns to the same cold, starkly beautiful emotional and geographical terrain he examined in 'The Sweet Hereafter'. This film seems like a mix of the low-key art-film and a standard-issue police procedural, with odd narrative choices that leave the viewer confused. It leaves the grand tragedy of 'The Sweet Hereafter', its schoolbus full of children disappearing over an icy slope, for a more private, personal tragedy. The narrative jumps back and forth through the eight-year period of Cassandra's disappearance. In 2005, a detective named Jeffrey -- Scott Speedman -- joins an RCMP unit tracking missing children and crimes against children. His new commanding officer is Nicole -- Rosario Dawson -- whom he will later become romantically involved with. Cassandra, meanwhile, is very much alive. Having endured years of terrible abuse at the hands of her abductor, she is now old enough that he has lost interest in her sexually, thankfully. Mika is a monstrous anomaly, but incredibly, he belongs to a group of like-minded freaks in an online pedophilia ring. They have a bizarre fixation with the mundane stories of their victims, and Cassandra is kept alive to not just tell these stories to an audience of perverts, but to someday ensnare another young girl. Kevin Durand is excellent, as usual, interpreting yet another psychotic monster in an unusual way. He deserves credit for taking on such a thoroughly repugnant character in the first place. Mika is aided by a mysterious woman... the question hangs unanswered of whether or not she began as a victim herself, before turning into his accomplice. The pedophiles enjoy witnessing the agony of Cassandra's parents; Mika has installed camera's in the rooms where Tina works, and he begins leaving significant objects for her to find, and witness her pain and confusion. Matthew feels compelled to traverse the snow-covered highways, hoping for a miracle, that the next girl he sees hitch-hiking will be his daughter.

The problem with 'The Captive' is that it involves too many characters and subplots... and leaves almost all of them unaddressed. It's not that the story is over-sized or convoluted; other films have juggled far larger casts and far more complicated stories with ease. But there were obviously scenes cut from the film, in an attempt to keep down the running-time. Whatever choices were made in the cutting room, they were issues that should have been addressed in the screenplay, because you can't solve every problem with editing. Jumping forward and back in time is a device that can be intriguing, dropping clues to quickly grab attention, i.e. the early scene in which Jeffrey is interrogating Mika's boss (Bruce Greenwood, portraying one of the several characters who serve no function whatsoever, except perhaps as red herrings in a previous draft that didn't give away the mystery immediately) and the audience learns that Nicole has gone missing in 2013... but since her character doesn't appear until afterward, it's easy to miss this detail, especially if you haven't been paying attention to the dates that pop up briefly every scene. When it does rewind to 2005, it doesn't help much to propel the plot. Nicole heads up the team of RCMP detectives working on cases involving children; Jeffrey is the hotshot with the 'excellent clearance rate' who has transferred from homicide for mysterious reasons; that doesn't stop her from 'testing' him with some awful piece of child porn, then acting smug when he expresses disgust and outrage, as if he didn't realize that this would be a part of his mandate in a squad investigating child abuse. Then both Jeffrey and the viewer meet the eclectic group of cops on the team, in the contrived manner of NCIS or CSI: Miami -- the tech guy, the science guy, the pattern recognition guy... wait, the what? So they dump out a large puzzle on the table in a jumbled mess, and he soon describes in detail the finished picture on the box. 'That's impressive', says the new guy. Sure is. Too bad this 'pattern recognition' character does absolutely nothing through the rest of the film. There are other examples that I won't get into, for spoilage reasons. Needless to say, I was surprised by the seriously flawed story-telling; the chronological confusion is exacerbated by the number of 'jumps' - 2005, 2006, 2011, 2012, 2013... it's an amateurish mistake. Maybe I expect too much from Atom Egoyan. Usually, I associate Egoyan with prestigious, artistic film-making, but I don't think that reputation exists south of the border. In Canada, he deserves as much credit as David Cronenberg and Denis Villeneuve for establishing a Canadian cinematic identity, for 'Exotica' and 'The Sweet Hereafter' alone. But that was a long time ago. If I didn't know that Egoyan directed this film, I probably wouldn't have been so patient with the disjointed, off-putting mess that is made of the story. There are inconsistencies in the tale that no brilliant performance, no poignant visual metaphors can balance out.

Nevertheless, it's beautifully shot, it has deep emotional resonancy, and it's suspenseful, even if it's not prime Egoyan; if you're willing to be patient with an often frustrating narrative, it's worth watching.

I'm not familiar with Atom Egoyan's body of work, but I was aware that his recent films haven't been too well received, this one included. THE CAPTIVE has some great, lurid subject material but it lacked any emotional depth and its non-linear construction does more to hurt than help it. The basic story is that Matthew Lane's (Ryan Reynolds) daughter disappeared eight years ago, but tantalizing clues keep popping up that seem to indicate she may still be alive. One thing I think was done well was the way in which the villain was portrayed. Normally, this type of movie would be sort of like a whodunit, but instead you get a pretty good look at what a child predator is like. Too bad that character motivations are never really explored beyond a father desperately wanting his child back, and the non-linear structure absolutely kills any character development as you never see the progression the characters take. There is also very little suspense due to this same thing, and to make matters worse the way in which things are wrapped up was a little too clean in my opinion. Not that there's anything wrong with happy endings, but for such a downbeat movie I expected something a little more bittersweet. However, despite the story problems the film was generally well-acted, except for the actress portraying Matt's daughter Cassandra (Alexia Fast). Something about her line delivery was just off. Ryan Reynolds gives a pretty good serious performance and Kevin Durand was wonderfully off-kilter and creepy as the villain. Mireille Enos (the mother) was ok, but I didn't particularly like when her character resorted to the typical hysterics. It was a little too over the top, to be honest. However, the real standout in the cast was Rosario Dawson. The parts of the story which focused on her cop character were the most interesting to me. In regards to technical aspects, the film was well-shot and had an interesting visual style. The entire film takes place in winter, and there were lots of beautiful shots of snowy landscapes. The score was decent too, and fit the material rather well. Overall, this was a well-made film on a technical level but it has some story and character issues which make it less than it could have been. I'd say that this is something you would be justified in skipping, though, especially when there's better similar films, like PRISONERS.

The plot? Reynolds has the worst landscaping job in the world in permafrost Canada while Enos is the worst housekeeper in the world, spending her days pacing instead of cleaning hotel rooms. Both are unhappily married since their daughter was abducted while he bought pie. Enos overacts and screams at him for years while ignoring the incompetent police detectives who take turns in acting as a therapist to her and general pain in the ass to him. Hope is almost gone for the missing kid - and the audience - when a stereotypical child abductor hatches his master plan that has something to do with 1990s chatrooms and the Internet. And somehow he also put cameras in all the hotel rooms where Enos works. Meanwhile two police detectives spend times ewwwwing each other with sicko pictures instead of 'detecting' and seem to do everything other than solving crime. All of this happens in snow.

The film cannot decide what to focus on so it just does everything all at once, $4.99 buffet-style. We get some half-baked attempt at a police procedural though clearly the writers have never seen any other cop show let alone researched actual police work, so the twist is that the police are incompetent and just continuously harass the father of the missing kid. Then we get the half-cocked "my kid is missing" emotional story from Reynolds and Enos, neither of which has any material to work with and quickly exhaust the generic misery setup. The bad guy really isn't bad enough and looks like he could have been beaten up by the kid at any time if she'd just wanted to leave.

It's hard to put into words how bad this is but needless to say that The Captive manages to misfire on all cylinders at once. In taking an amateur script that should have never made production, it adds some wooden acting and risible dialog from actors who can do much better, and finally edits the mediocre result together with time-jumping tricks that are completely out of place in this sort of mundane made-for-TV story. Without a single likable character in the film or anyone behaving consistent with logic or reason (even the kidnappee seems pretty happy), it's a two-hour exercise in eye-rolling, face-palming and shouting insults at the TV.

If you hang in there hoping at least for a satisfying ending, disappointment is served in spades. The filmmakers, knowing that even a big train wreck has to end somehow, opt for the least plausible way to put this fire out - I shouldn't say too much in order to keep this spoiler-free but I just want you to know it doesn't get any better. In a year of pretty dreadful movie choices generally, The Captive will hopefully be first in line at the Razzie Awards. I would like to know how the bad guy got a power source to all those hidden cameras though.

Very good thriller that captured some very real aspects of child abduction.  The creepiness of Kevin Durands character (Mika) was complete.  He did an excellent job of portraying a sick twisted person.  It was a bit disjointed and it took a while to realize which scene was the past or present or a past scene that was before or after a different past scene (you can see how it gets confusing).  However, I was ultimately able to make heads and tails of it.  I thought Speekman's character (Detective) was a bit TOO antagonistic towards Ryan Renold's character(Matt).  However, my biggest gripe about the movie was they did not explore other characters and sub plots.

Who was Bruce Greenwood's character (Vince)?  Was he just the CEO of the company that Mika worked for?  Was he himself an abductor?  They certainly alluded to the possibility:  Mika started working FOR him at 15 years old.  At the benefit dinner they gave each other a few "knowing" glances.  Who was the woman with Mika (Vicky)?  When did Mika abduct her?  How did he turn her to work WITH him?  Was there a network of "subscriber's" watching Cass's mother (Tina) in the hotel rooms?  There were a lot of frustrating unanswered questions.

Then there is another aspect that does not reflect how I rate a movie at all, and maybe I am in a very small minority of people who would like to see this done more in movies like this:  I wish they would show the psychological effects on the characters after they've been rescued.  How did she (Cass) adapt to a normal life?  How did she do in school after that?  How was her emotional maturity and how was it stunted by an experience like this?

I guess I can do my own research of real life situations like this to learn of this, but I still don't think it would add a lot of time to the movie to do this more often, and maybe it wouldn't be interesting for most of the audience.  I know it's not essential for the plot, but I do think it would be a fascinating epilogue.

EXCELLENT film; writing, directing, acting all solid in my opinion.  I was glued to the television from beginning until the very end.  I'm so glad I didn't listen to negative reviews. I have been a fan of Atom Egoyan ever since his first film debut, "Exotica".  All of his films have been thought provoking, gripping, dark, and unsettling.  They all deal with a most difficult reality, one that none of us likes to think about, particularly those with children of our own; sexualization of children against their will.  It was no surprise to me to discover that he started out as a Stage Director.  I will admit it was difficult at times to follow the film in terms of time and space; past and present were hard to distinguish one from the other.  There were a few details about this film that did not make sense; for instance when the father discovers his daughter is missing why did he not look for footprints in the snow?  This would have been the first thing any person in their right mind would have considered right?  Easy for me to say, because clearly the guy was not in his right mind.  Also why did we not get to see police show up and look for clues, i.e. footprints, tire marks etc.??  I love Mireille Enos.  Watched her in "The Killing" and have followed her career also.  She was excellent in the role of the mother.  Even though Reynolds and Enos were not well matched as husband and wife, Reynolds gave a solid performance as the father.  Overall brilliant film, but one you really have to be in the mood for.  Not the kind of film you sit watching over popcorn.

Leaving his daughter in the car to run into a shop for a homemade pie, his waiting daughter lies down in the back seat to sort of "chill out". When the father returns with her favorite pie, she is gone. Frantically, he searches around the snow covered acreage, to no avail. He is grilled by the local law enforcement people, then his wife enters and goes into hysteria, pounding on him, blaming him for leaving their daughter alone in the car. Thus begins a riveting, tale of terror and breakdowns. The father has a record. One for assault. He and his wife are broke. He's a loser, and now he's lost his daughter, whom he adores. The plot thickens. You get to actually see the kidnapper, a real sick-o. You start to get in his mind.
I highly recommend this movie for its plot twists and fine acting. Some may not agree, but it was really different.

A surprisingly good movie.  It takes you down a dark and uncomfortable road, which isn't evident in the description -- that of child abduction and the predators behind it.  The story line is spiced with a little "Silence of the Lambs" feel to it (I won't put in any spoilers), with ultimately a happy ending which I found a good release from the well-acted tension that existed throughout.  It's a tense subject that I would recommend for adults, perhaps teenagers.  The movie doesn't expose the viewer to anything disturbing, but just enough hint of the reality of what goes on in this dark underworld.  Enough to make you think twice.

"The Captive" is not your usual "B" film kidnapping/imprisonment film. The beginning is a bit confusing as it utilizes flashbacks which I didn't realize for the first 30 minutes, making this film a confusing mess to begin with. I will briefly sort out the first 28 minutes of the movie. If you don't want to know...stop reading.

Cassandra (Alexia Fast/Peyton Kennedy) goes missing from the back of her daddy's truck cab. Matt (Ryan Reynolds ) her dad becomes suspect number one to the Niagara group "Anything For Love" headed by Nicole (Rosario Dawson). Matt's wife Tina (Mireille Enos) blames him and turns against him. Jeffry (Scott Speedman) who is part of Nicole's group is openly hostile toward Matt.

Cass has special privileges as a captive and provides her captor with a unique service which makes this film a bit different. Matt tries to find Cassandra on his own (better than when OJ went looking for the "real" killer) while the group works without Matt.

The film makes for a good "B" movie. It over utilizes the flash backs and really should have never had the flashback scene near the end which had me scratch my head...but wasn't she? How did? Oh a flashback. Of what? A day? A gimmick they really didn't need. Or was it a trick?

Notice that the creep in this movie takes pleasure in watching the mother's anguish. He not only spies on her in the hotel rooms, he also gaslights her by leaving a hairbrush and a tooth in one of the rooms, so he can watch her reactions on video. This guy is not only into kidnapping little girls, he's also into emotional and psychological mind control. He is in control of the girl, the father and the mother. It makes him feel superior. It's thrilling to him. He enjoys it. He's the cat toying with the mouse. The puppeteer controlling the puppets. The ultimate reality entertainer. Real people are his dolls. He is playing doll-house. Dressing and undressing his "dolls" as he sees fit. (This guy is not a man. He is a creep). "Watching mommy twist." "That's not a bad idea for a reality show." "There's a kidnapper and there is a watcher." "Or watchers." "Maybe even subscribers." "A whole new class of freaks." (Thank you, A24 Films). Read Among Enemies; the surveillance is doable. Technically it can be done.

Pretty insitefull look into the reality of a family who's child has been abducted and left with absolutely no idea of how or why. The entire cast did an awesome job in the roles they each played. This isn't an action film, is it an honest, heart moving story, about loss, grief, and the personal struggles of not only the family but the dectectives who have been left to deal with this kind of situation. What matters the most about this movie is the ending. Everyone comes home... Most of the families who have found themselves in this situation do not get this kind of blessing. They say the first 24 hours after an abduction are the most critical in finding a child. Imagine if you will, eight years, eight years of not knowing anything. I can't even begin to understand how in real life these families can go on after something like this happens... Well Done Mr Reynolds and all of those involved in the making of this movie. This is the kind of story that needs to be heard around the world. Never loose Hope.

I went back and forth on giving this one or two stars.  In the end I gave it two as it was artistically shot and the acting was quite good.  Otherwise . . . I just could not like this movie.  I understand what they were trying to do but the basic plot has rather large holes in it.  The way it is shot back and forth over three different time periods with absolutely no indication of switching from one period to the next could have been interesting but quickly got tiring.  It was very difficult to have empathy for any of the characters - the bad guys were really really bad so I guess they got that right . . .  But the father mostly came across as a loser, the mother rather insane, the police officers against the parents . . . just not a lot to root for here.  They ended the movie obviously trying to not have it be a "Hollywood ending" but ended up just kind of dragging it out.  I guess it did a good job in really trying hard to install fear in parents, but even that was based around a situation full of plot holes.  So, I really can't recommend this one - which is a pity as I like Ryan Reynolds and can see he was going for a role in what was supposed to be a much darker, artistic "serious acting chops film."  I almost wish it had been a bit less interesting so I would have stopped watching it rather then continue all the way through.

Stranger danger. Creepy opera fans (and by the way, if you're going to use Mozart as your musical motif, don't just rip off the best songs from Amadeus--dig into Wolfie's catalog a bit, won't you?). Snow. Lots and lots of fluffy Canadian snow. What should have been gut-wrenching was plodding and passably dreadful. Had this been in the service of information, or even drama, it might have been OK, but like the ice-slicked roads of the Great White North, there was nothing here to provide traction. It appeared to be at least three separate and only occasionally parallel stories, but the editing booth was attacked by honey badgers and the resulting scraps had to be assembled at random.

This is not a terrible movie. Elements of it, in fact, are excellent--although much of what's good in "Captive" has been done better elsewhere. My only real complaint is that it's not entertaining. Now. I don't demand that every movie I see BE entertaining. I loved "Tim's Vermeer," and that was a documentary about a man trying to copy a painting. But if a movie is going to be billed as some kind of "thriller," it better conjur up more emotion than an Oxygen drama.

This was a very slow drama that was hurt severally by the back and forth time changes in the first part of the movie.  Very poorly edited and kept the viewers confused as to what was going on.  Also the writers had Scott Speedman's cop so dislikeable that they probably could have dropped the role from the film and not hurt anything.  What also hurt the back and forth time changes was that there were no apparent changes in looks or dress of Ryan Reynolds during the 8 year gap.  You couldn't tell by looking at him that you were in one period or the other, it all looked the same.  So too for the rest of the characters.  He played a father who stops at a roadside diner to run in and get a cherry pie for desert that night and when he returns to the car his daughter has been kidnapped.
Eight years later they still haven't found her.  For some inexplicable reason Speedman's character is sure that Reynolds did it himself.  Not a bad flick, but certainly dry.  Maybe interesting for those that enjoy that style of film.
